<HEADLINE> Indian Government Urged to Review Moratorium Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Bharatiya Janata
Party (BJP) asked the Indian government Saturday to review its
offer of unilateral moratorium on further nuclear tests, made
after the nuclear tests last May.
</P>
<P>
A resolution adopted by BJP National Executive Saturday
asserted that India had the strength and capacity to withstand and
survive the economic sanctions imposed by many countries and
international organizations following the nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
The National Executive began a three-day meeting Friday in
BJP's power base in Jaipur, capital city of northwest Rajasthan.
</P>
<P>
According to the Press Trust of India (PTI), the executives
favored reviewing the decision of the BJP-led government on
nuclear moratorium if future developments jeopardized India's
national strategic and security interests.
</P>
<P>
The resolution adopted by the executives asked the government
not to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty on the ground that
it is "discriminatory".
</P>
<P>
Members of the Executive were critical of the failure of the
coalition government to curb mounting prices in the country since
the nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
An economic resolution adopted Saturday by the executives
blamed the price rise on the previous governments and unfavorable
weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
PTI quoted party sources as saying that the BJP-led coalition
came in for sharp criticism by some members at the meeting for its
failure to ease the price rise.
</P>
<P>
The BJP elite suggested that the public distribution system be
streamlined and strengthened and distribution of essential
commodities at reasonable rates be ensured so that the common
people are relieved of the burden of back-breaking prices and
shortages created by hoarders.
</P>
<P>
The prices of essential commodities have skyrocketed since the
BJP-led government came to power last March, especially since the
S22085HAB211I0822QU00:3500:381248
country conducted nuclear tests in May, with prices of some
YCC085HAB211I0822QU00:3500:381248
commodities increasing by more than 10 times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
