<HEADLINE> Kabila's Envoy Late for Pretoria Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The representative of
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) President Laurent Kabila, will
arrive in South Africa late Saturday for talks with Uganda and Rwanda
over the DRC crisis, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
South African presidential spokesman Parks Mankahlana said DRC
Justice Minister Mwenze Kongolo had left the DRC in a cargo plane at 4
p.m.
</P>
<P>
Kongolo was sent in Kabila's place as Kabila was unable to attend
the talks for health reasons, Mankahlana said earlier Saturday.
</P>
<P>
SAPA earlier quoted a Waterkloof air base official as saying the
DRC representative would not be able to be in South Africa Saturday.
Waterkloof is the place where delegations for the peace talks are
expected.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and Rwandan President Pasteur
Bizimungu had no intention of ditching the talks and were presently
locked in a meeting with South African President Nelson Mandela, said
Mankahlana.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda were accused by Kabila of supporting rebels in
the DRC, but the two countries have denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's peace talks were aimed at finding a peaceful solution
to the crisis in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
It was hoped that the meeting would produce a peace proposal which
would be tabled at Sunday's Southern African Development Community
summit.
</P>
<P>
Another head of state in the region who has been invited to
Saturday's talks, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, refused to
attend the meeting. He also refused to be present at Sunday's summit.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe distanced himself from South Africa, which believes in a
peaceful solution to the military conflict in the DRC. Mugabe had
reportedly sent troops to the DRC to help Kabila quell the revolt.
</P>
<P>
Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos, who is also in favor of
military intervention, would not attend Sunday's summit for "medical
reasons". 
</P>
</TEXT>
