<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni Concerned About Situation in DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has expressed concern about the events unfolding in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the State House here Saturday said
that it is Museveni who previously suggested that a regional
summit be held to discuss the volatile situation in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, the summit in Victoria Falls of Zimbabwe
earlier this month did not decisively put a halt to the fighting
so as to solve the problems politically.
</P>
<P>
President Museveni has been in contact with many African
leaders, but consensus has not yet emerged, said the press
release.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some countries are beginning to intervene in
democratic Congo without waiting for the consensus to emerge,
probably due to the fact that the anti-Kabila alliance has been
gaining ground rapidly, it said.
</P>
<P>
Museveni sees dangers in foreign intervention, the release
said, adding that he urges all external players to restrain
themselves and to hold a summit meeting quickly to crystalize the
lacking consensus.
</P>
<P>
If unilateral intervention intensifies, Uganda may be forced
to take actions to protect its own security interests, said the
Ugandan president.
</P>
<P>
The press release said Uganda's main interests in the DRC are
threefold: to prevent Sudan from infiltrating terrorism into
Uganda; to stop the Interahamwe of Rwanda from using the
Congolese territory to kill people in the southwestern district
of Kisoro; together with international community, to avoid
massacres like those in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
It once again refuted reports of Ugandan invasion of
democratic Congo.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has been having two battalions in the DRC to combat
rebels and lawless elements according to mutual understanding
with Kabila's administration. This is the only extent of our
involvement in the Congo up to now, it said.
</P>
<P>
The press release pointed out that President Museveni still
hopes the problem in the DRC can be solved politically,
suggesting that regional summit meetings be held to call for a
cease-fire to be followed by talks between the DRC government and
its armed opponents as well as other political forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
