<HEADLINE> Iran's Carpet Export Records 30 Years' Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The export of Iran's famous
hand-woven carpets has plunged into the lowest level in 30 years,
the evening daily Resalat reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The export dropped to 114.5 million U.S. dollars during the
first four months of the current Iranian year (starting from March
21), showing 31.7 percent decrease compared with the same period
of last Iranian year, the paper quoted Khosrow Sobhe, a member of
the Carpet Exporters Union, as saying.
</P>
<P>
If hurdles on the way were removed with a change in the
country's regulations on exports, Iran's annual carpet export
could reach 1 billion U.S. dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
Without going to details about the hurdles, Sobhe said that at
present, Iran only covers 30 percent of the world carpet exports
which stands at about 2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some 35 years ago, Iran dominated over half of the world
demand, but the rate sharply declined due to the country's
complicated export procedures and challenges from other
carpet-exporting countries.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Iran's carpet export stood at 1.64 billion dollars,
but the figure dropped to 561 million dollars in 1997, Iranian
officials announced earlier.
</P>
<P>
According to Sobhe, nearly 2 million Iranians are currently
employed in carpet weaving industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
