<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM Meets With Sudanese Opposition Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa Saturday met with Sudanese opposition leader and the
meeting "dealt with consultations and understanding on the events
in Khartoum," Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from the meeting, Mohamed Osma Mirghani, leader of
Sudan's National Democratic Alliance (NDA), the umbrella group of
all opposition factions in the north and south, declined to give
any comments on Sudan's developments following the U.S. strikes
against a pharmaceutical plant near Khartoum Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said the opposition has spelled out its stance on the
U.S. strike against alleged terrorist-associated Sudanese
facilities in a statement issued earlier.
</P>
<P>
The statement Mirghani mentioned was issued following a meeting
of the opposition groups in Cairo Saturday morning. It urged the
formation of a fact-finding mission to collect evidence of Sudan's
chemical weapons production, and supported an Egyptian call for
convening an international conference on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. fired cruise missiles Thursday night at a
pharmaceutical factory near Khartoum in what it claimed
retaliation for bombings on August 7 of U.S. embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has accused Sudan of sponsoring international
terrorism and claimed that the factory was manufacturing chemical
weapons agents that could be used by Islamic militants to launch
new attacks against U.S. targets.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrea-based NDA held three days of meetings here starting
from August 15. It is the first such meeting ever hosted by Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, which has a border dispute and other hanging issues with
its southern neighbor, had kept a low profile in the 15-year civil
conflicts in Sudan but is apparently adjusting the stance as
fightings have escalated and the famine crisis in southern Sudan
degenerated.
</P>
<P>
The war between the Sudanese government troops and rebel forces
fighting for autonomy in southern Sudan since 1983, combined with
famine, had taken a toll of more than 1.5 million lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
