<HEADLINE> GCC Keen to See East Africa Stabilized, Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) is keen on finding a peaceful solution to the
border dispute between Ethiopia and Eritrea so that East Africa
YPR147CAB072I22TAQL01:5001:531150
S25147CAB072I22TAQL01:5001:531150
can be stable, GCC Secretary General Jamil Al-Hujailan said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Hujailan made this remark during his meeting in Riyadh with the
Ethiopian ambassador to Saudi Arabia, Mohammad Ibrahim, Kuwait
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A news release issued by the GCC's Secretariat General said
that Hujailan was briefed about the latest developments of the
Ethiopian-Eritrean crisis.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the GCC and Ethiopia were also discussed
during the meeting, the press statement said.
</P>
<P>
The crisis erupted between the two east African countries last
May when Eritrean troops entered a number of disputed border
areas, which led to heavy military confrontations between
Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Mediation efforts by the international community have not
brought to an end to the crisis, as Ethiopia was still insisting
for an Eritrean withdrawal before any direct negotiation, a matter
of which is rejected by Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, during its 67th ministerial meeting last June in
Riyadh, had called on the two countries to solve their dispute
through dialogs and urged them to halt armed confrontations to
achieve regional stability.
</P>
<P>
GCC groups Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, and the
United Arab Emirates (UAE). 
</P>
