<HEADLINE> Museveni Leaves for Summit in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni left for South Africa Saturday morning at the invitation
of President Nelson Mandela to attend a regional summit on the
situation in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the State House Saturday evening
said the president left for Pretoria from the northern district
of Gulu where he was on a working visit.
</P>
<P>
Considering the worsening situation in the DRC and the
divisions among the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
over military intervention in DRC, Mandela invited presidents of
Uganda, Rwanda, the DRC, Angola and Zimbabwe to discuss the
issue.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe supports sending military aid to help DRC
President Laurent Kabila while some other countries in SADC do
not like this choice.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that President Kabila sent his ministers to
represent him at the talks because a crowded timetable prevented
him from attending.
</P>
<P>
President Museveni was accompanied by Amama Mbabazi, the
Minister of State for Regional Cooperation. 
</P>
