<HEADLINE> Egypt: Anti-Terrorism Acts Should Have Legitimacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said on Saturday that actions aimed at stubbing out
terrorism should be ratified by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Moussa called on the U.N. Security
Council to take necessary measures to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"Our position is that all measures taken to confront terrorism
should be through international legitimacy and under the umbrella
of the U.N.," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. Security Council remains the supreme world authority
charged with maintaining world peace and security," he said.
</P>
<P>
In its response to Thursday's U.S. air strikes on alleged
terrorist-associated facilities in Sudan and Afghanistan, Egypt on
Friday called on the U.N. to host a world summit on combating
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
It urged the Security Council to take appropriate measures in
line with the U.N. Charter to fight and root out terrorism and
bring those responsible to justice.
</P>
<P>
"Since that terrorism wreaks havoc in many world communities,
Egypt believes that the whole world, instead of just one country,
must agree on a definitive measure in this respect. And the
Security Council is just the quarter to decide on that," Moussa
told reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
