<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government
Saturday dismissed claims by Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
rebels that they had shot down two Zimbabwean MIG jet fighters as
they advanced toward capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
"We have no MIG fighters in the DRC. For them (rebels) to
M14-82NBB118i0822ql02:1502:151141
have shot them down, they have to have been there in the first
place," Presidential spokesman George Charamba told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Charamba dismissed the rebel claims as " propaganda", adding
that "our deployment in the DRC did not have that dimension (MIG
fighters)."
</P>
<P>
Congo (k) Rebel foreign affairs spokesman Bizima Karaha
Saturday told reporters in its headquarters in the eastern city
of Goma that the two Zimbabwean jets had been shot down on the
western front.
</P>
<P>
"Just this morning we have shot two of their (Zimbabwean) jet
fighters," Karaha said.
</P>
<P>
"We have shot them down and this is just a warning," he said,
adding that the planes were Zimbabwean and were hit on "the
western front."
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government, while acknowledging its deployment
to prop up DRC President Laurent Kabila, has declined to give
details.
</P>
<P>
Speculative reports said Saturday that Zimbabwe
deployed as many as 900 combat troops and aircrafts to help
Kabila quell the rebellion.  
