<HEADLINE> Mugabe Not Keen on Summit on DRC Crisis: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe has no plan to attend a twin summit on the crisis in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) called by South African
President Nelson Mandela, presidential spokesman said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman George Charamba told reporters that there are no
indications of a presidential trip to South Africa for Mugabe to
attend the emergency meeting of leaders from Uganda, Rwanda, the
DRC and Zimbabwe in Pretoria Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This meeting will be followed by a full Southern African
Development Community (SADC) summit at the same venue Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"I have no information to the effect that the president is
leaving for South Africa," Charamba said. "At the moment there
is no trip in the offing, maybe something will come up later."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe insisted that it will not participate at both
the emergency meeting and the SADC summit unless four other
countries aiding the embattled DRC government -- Angola, Namibia,
Tanzania and Zambia -- are also present.
</P>
<P>
Nine SADC defense ministers who met in Harare at the beginning
of this week agreed that the region should support the embattled
DRC government and bring back peace and order to the central
African country of more than 40 million people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
