<HEADLINE> Nigerian New Cabinet Sworn in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's newly-appointed cabinet
ministers were sworn in Saturday in the capital Abuja and the
post of Minister for Petroleum Resources is still vacant, the
Nigerian TV Authority said.
</P>
<P>
A source from the State House was quoted as saying that the
activities of the Oil Ministry will be handled by a special
adviser under the presidency.
</P>
<P>
At the swearing-in ceremony, Nigerian Head of State Abdulsalam
Abubakar urged his ministers to shun corruption during the period
before the power hand-over on May 29 next year.
</P>
<P>
"We will therefore closely monitor all of you, as well as any
public officer given positions of trust and responsibility, to
ensure that their assignments are not used as springboards for
launch into criminal affluence," Abubakar stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to the assignment of minister portfolio,Ismaila
Usman, a central banker, was named finance minister while former
ambassador to the United States Ignatius Olisemeka appointed
foreign affairs minister.
</P>
<P>
The 31-member new cabinet was announced on August 20, one
month after the old cabinet was dissolved following the sudden
death of former head of state Sani Abacha on June 8.
</P>
<P>
Officials in Abuja explained that the long delay in naming the
cabinet ministers was to ensure the posts were shared out fairly
among various regions and tribes in the west African country.
</P>
</TEXT>
