<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Welcomes Egypt's Anti-Terrorism Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Ambassador in Cairo Ahmed
Abdel Halim said Saturday that Sudan welcomed an Egyptian proposal
for convening an international conference on combating terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks following talks here with Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa, during which they briefed each other on their
governments' stances on Thursday's U.S. air raids on alleged
terrorist-related facilities in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., accusing Sudan of sponsoring international terrorism,
fired cruise missiles Thursday night at a pharmaceutical factory
in Khartoum in what it claimed retaliation for bombings on August
7 of its embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign Minister Moussa told me that Egypt is keen on dealing
with terrorism within international legitimacy and does not
approve any unilateral measure in this regard," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Halim said that Sudan had signed the Arab Anti-terrorism
Pact and relevant international documents. "It welcomes Egypt's
proposal (of an international anti-terrorism conference,)" he added.
</P>
<P>
He said Egypt's delegate to the U.N. has voiced Egypt's
sympathy with Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador denounced the U.S. attack as "unjustified and
not based on any evidence."
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. administration tried to launch an act of thuggery
after it had been accused of being unable to protect its embassies
and citizens abroad and following the scandal facing the
U.S. president," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the ambassador, the Sudanese factory which came
under attack was a pharmaceutical plant, where the United Nations
contracted with the Sudanese government to purchase the produced
medicine for the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Besides, it was owned by a Sudanese national called Salah
Idriss and not Saudi billionaire Osama Ben Laden, the No. 1
terrorist wanted by the U.S. for a series of terrorist attacks, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. claimed that the factory, financed by Laden, was
manufacturing chemical weapons agents that could be used by
Islamic militants to launch new attacks against U.S. targets.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has asked the U.N. Security Council and the
U.N. secretary general to dispatch a team to get acquainted with
the bombed factory's capabilities, the ambassador added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Sudan, the two Nile neighbors, have been in disputes
over border and other hanging issues, and traded accusations of
harboring militants against each other.
</P>
<P>
Cairo, for the first time, hosted last week a meeting of
Sudan's opposition parties, viewed as a policy shift towards
enhanced involvement in its southern neighbor's 15-year civil
conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
