<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Launch Tsetse Fly Wipe-Out in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The ministry of agriculture
of Ethiopia announces Saturday that a new project aimed at
eradicating Tsetse fly from Ethiopia will commence in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Gebre-Medhin Belay, Head of Planning and Program Department of
the ministry told reporters that the project will be implemented
in Deddesa and Wamma rift valleys and Abay basins with an annual
cost of 17.6 million Birr (2.5 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Belay disclosed that the Ethiopian government plans to rid
550,000 hectares of land in Deddesa and Wamma rift valleys of
Tsetse fly and trypanosomiasis in four years beginning in 1999.
</P>
<P>
He said that Tsetse fly is affecting 18 percent of the
country, covering 200,000 square kilometers of land. Ten million
cattle, 6.1 million sheep and goats, one million camel and 1.2
million pack animals are exposed to trypanosomiasis in Ethiopia,
for which the country loses over 200 million U.S. Dollars
annually.
</P>
<P>
The project to be undertaken through the agreement reached
between the Ethiopian government and the European Economic
Commission is part of the east African sub-region program
coordinated by the Organization of African Unity, Belay said.
</P>
<P>
The project will also be carried out in Kenya, Uganda
and Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
