<HEADLINE> Jordan's PM Denounces Terrorism, Proposes Dialog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Fayez
Tarawneh Saturday denounced terrorism, but also criticized the
resort to force to settle problems.
</P>
<P>
Jordan condemned all forms of terrorism whether they were
committed by individuals or organized entities, because they led
to the killing of innocent people, Tarawneh said in a press
statement.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government proposed that all conflicting parties
should drop acts of terrorism and open dialog, especially
security dialog, said Tarawneh, who was just appointed prime
minister on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh expressed the hope that all the countries in the world
would talk to each other openly in the same spirit and not rely
on force to settle conflicts, adding that the international and
the United Nations Charter should be the decisive factor in this
respect.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark after Thursday's U.S. missile attacks on a
number of suspected terrorist-related sites in Afghanistan and
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prime minister welcomed the Sudanese
government's decision to invite the world media to visit the site
in Khartoum that the U.S. missile attacked.
</P>
<P>
Sudan said that the site was only a pharmaceutic plant for
producing medicines and did not accommodate any equipment for
manufacturing chemical arms or poisonous gas.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. alleged that the site was a military base of the
terrorists lead by Saudi "dissident" Osama Ben Laden who
reportedly masterminded and sponsored the explosions of the
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Jordan maintains close relations with both Sudan and the U.S..
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
