<HEADLINE> Iranian President Condemns U.S. Attack on Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami on Saturday condemned the Thursday U.S. attack on a
Sudanese factory and announced his support for Khartoum to
complain against Washington.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with his Sudanese counterpart Omar
Ahmed al-Bashir, Khatami termed the U.S. attack as an obvious
aggression against Sudan and violated the international laws and
the world's security.
</P>
<P>
He expressed sympathy with the Sudanese government and nation
over the issue, the state-run television reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. launched simultaneous missile attacks Thursday night
on what it described as "terrorist-related" targets in Sudan and
Afghanistan following the bombings of the U.S. embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government termed the U.S. attack as "a barbaric
act."
</P>
<P>
As the current chairman of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC), the Iranian president said that the attack on an
OIC member should be double condemned.
</P>
<P>
Expressing regret over the explosions at the U.S. embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania, he condemned Washington for using the
incidents as a pretext to violate the international laws.
</P>
<P>
He announced support for Sudan to lodge complaint against the
U.S. in the United Nations, particularly the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bashir briefed Khatami on the attack and said the
U.S. targeted a pharmaceutical factory and killed many innocent
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
