<HEADLINE> Wild Animals Threaten Security in Tanzanian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Wild animals are posing
threats to residents in the Tunduru District in the Ruvuma Region,
southern Tanzania, a local government official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Since January this year, wild animals have killed 15 people in the
Lukumbule and Malasi Divisions in Tunduru, the district Commissioner
Tatu Rutta told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Of the victims, eight have been killed by crocodiles, five by
elephants and two by lions, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a bitter tone, the district commissioner said that wild
beasts are a threat in the district, sandwiched by the Selous Game
Reserve and River Ruvuma which are densely populated by wild animals.
</P>
<P>
She said apart from threatening people's lives, the wild animals
are devastating agricultural crops in farms and even eating those
stored in locally constructed storage facilities.
</P>
<P>
Every year more than 30 percent of food crops are destroyed by the
animals, thus causing food shortages, she said.
</P>
<P>
The official said shortage of game officers is one of the factors
contributing to the insecurity of local residents and their farms. She
said each division of the district has only one game officer, adding
that more are needed for the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has a good reputation for wildlife conservation, but
people in the east African country often complain that they are
threatened by wild animals and are inadequately compensated by the
government for their losses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
