<HEADLINE> Arab League to Meet on U.S. Strike in Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) Council will
hold an extraordinary session Monday at the level of chief
delegates to look into the U.S. shelling of a pharmaceutical
factory in Sudan, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Delegates to the Cairo-based AL will seek a unified Arab stance
on this score, said Ahmad Bin Heli, AL assistant secretary general.
</P>
<P>
AL secretary general Esmat Abdel Meguid has received a
memorandum from Sudanese Foreign Minister Mustafa Osman Ismail
calling for holding an emergency session by the league council, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Meguid also received a report from the Sudanese foreign
minister on the scope of damage done to the vaccine-producing
factory.
</P>
<P>
In the report, he further expressed Sudan's readiness to
receive an international fact-finding mission to explore the
nature of the factory.
</P>
<P>
The AL has strongly condemned the U.S. bombardment Thursday of
a pharmaceutical plant in the Sudanese capital Khartoum which left
a number of civilians dead and flattened a facility providing the
country with 50 percent of its needs of medicines.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released Friday, the AL Secretariat said it
deemed the unwarranted action a serious aggression on a sovereign
Arab country and a flagrant violation of the international law and
conventions and the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
The AL urged the U.S., as a permanent Security Council member
and a super power shouldering the responsibility for maintaining
world peace and security, to respect international legitimacy and
desist from such acts that violate world countries' sovereignty
and encourage acts of violence.
</P>
<P>
The statement voiced support for Sudan in the face of threats
to its stability, unity and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. launched the attacks in what it claimed retaliation
for the bombings of its embassies in Kenya and Tanzania on August
7. It has accused Sudan of sponsoring international terrorism and
claimed the factory was manufacturing chemical weapons agents that
could be used by Islamic militants to launch new attacks against
U.S. targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
