<HEADLINE> Over Half Million Angolan Children Vaccinated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- In the first phase of the
national anti-polio campaign in Angola, about 550,000 children
under the age of five years have taken vaccine drops, the Angolan
health ministry said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that nearly three million Angolan children
under five will be given polio vaccine free of charge during
the anti-polio drive.
</P>
<P>
Starting from Wednesday, local media in capital Luanda
launched a mass mobilization drive, calling on the parents to
bring their children to the vaccination centers. Leaders of
governments, churches and mass organizations personally gave
drops of vaccine against polio to the children.
</P>
<P>
It is difficult for African countries to implement a national
vaccination campaign. Therefore, the health ministry mobilized
3,900 people in 317 teams to serve the children around the
southern African country.
</P>
<P>
Some of the wokers had to pass a long journey to the remote
areas, risking the scattered land mines and rampant
banditry.
</P>
<P>
Because of the prolonged civil war, malnutrition and various
diseases, Angola has the highest child mortality rate in the
world -- one of every four children in Angola dies before the age
of five years.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO), the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) and some non-governmental organizations
have provided their supports for the anti-polio campaign.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the drive will begin at the end of
September this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
