<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The Central Bank of Yemen (CBY) said it will cast in
the market a new 1,000-riyal (7.46 U.S. dollars) bank note, the
biggest of its kind in Yemen.
</P>
<P>
The CBY printed the new bank note in Germany with special
characteristics including a number of secret features and other
technical features that can protect it against damage, Saturday's
Arabic daily Al-Hayat quoted a CBY official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The CBY will declare the date of starting the circulation of
the new bank note soon, the official added.
</P>
<P>
The bank had issued a 500-riyal bank note in February, 1997,
and a 200-riyal bank note in 1996 under the financial and fiscal
reforms, he noted.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The damage inflicted by environmental pollution in
Morocco is estimated at 8.2 percent of the gross national products
(GDP) or 4 billion U.S. dollars annually, apart from the
non-economic damage, according to the lastest statistics of the
Ministry of Environment.
</P>
<P>
The damage resulting from the liquid waste exceeds 2.2 billion
dollars a year and is also on the rise due to the increasing
population, Saturday's Al-Hayat newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the environment deterioration in
Morocco and worldwide to natural causes such as desertification
and human causes such as the industrial liquid and solid waste and
gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Port Said Container Plant, an affiliate of the
Holding Co. for Transport on the Mediterranean Sea, is expected to
