<P>
AMMAN -- The Yugoslavian Airlines (YA) will begin to operate on
Sunday one weekly flight from Amman to Belgrade and then from
Belgrade to other European cities, Jordan's official news agency
Petra Saturday quoted an official of the YA bureau in Amman as
saying Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The YA intends to facilitate tourism and business travel
between the two countries by launching such a flight, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's trade deficit in the first seven months of
this year dropped to about 3.7 billion U.S. dollars, 219 million
less than the figure in the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest data release of the customs department,
exports in the first seven months of 1998 stood at 375 million
dollars while imports reached 4.061 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The World Bank has decided to set up an office in
Beirut in order to further provide Lebanon with a financial
support for its post-civil war reconstruction, the Daily Star
reported.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank started lending money to Lebanon in 1992 after
the country embarked on a reconstruction process after the
1975-1990 civil war.
</P>
<P>
A total of 667 million U.S. dollars in loans and guarantees
have been approved for Lebanon. But only 191 million dollars, or
28 percent, had actually been spent up to last June. 
</P>
