<HEADLINE> S. Leone Frees 32 Held for Alleged Collaboration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone has freed 22 senior
police officers and 10 civilians who had been suspected of
helping the ousted military junta of Major Johnny Paul Koromah, a
report from Freetown said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the state radio as saying that the detainees
who had been in jail since last March were released Friday from
prisons in the Sierra Leonean capital.
</P>
<P>
Their detention followed the February ousting by the West
African peace-keeping force of the military junta that seized
power from elected president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in a coup in May
last year.
</P>
<P>
The released officers included a senior police commissioner,
Christopher John, and the former head of the paramilitary Special
Security Division (SSD), the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vice-President Joe Demby Saturday launched the
Disarmament, Demobilization and Rehabilitation (DDR) program at
Lungi, 15 kilometers from Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The DDR program which is sponsored by the United Nations (UN),
will involve over 2,000 former combatants who will be demobilized
and handed over to the U.N. observer mission in Sierra Leone, the
report said. 
</P>
