<HEADLINE> US Against Military Intervention in DRC Crisis: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's
special envoy Howard Wolpe said here Saturday that the U.S.
government insists on a diplomatic and political solution to the
crisis in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) instead of a
military one.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Luanda International Airport, Wolpe said that
the U.S. government fears that the situation in the DRC could "be
out of control", hoping countries concerned would "create
conditions for a lasting peace there."
</P>
<P>
Wolpe conveyed to Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos a
letter form President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy noted that diplomatic and political solution is
the only way out and his government has ruled out the possibility
of a military solution to the DRC crisis.
</P>
<P>
Wolpe arrived here Saturday for a three-day visit to the
southern African country. He held talks with Angolan Deputy
Foreign Minister Jorge Chicote at the airport.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy is also scheduled to visit Uganda, South Africa
and Rwanda, where he will urge countries in the region to press
for a ceasefire in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
The August 2 rebellion led by the Tutsi Banyamulenge soldiers,
threatens to engulf the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Development Community (SADC) has
reportedly decided to give military assistance to DRC President
Laurent Kabila, but some member states including South Africa and
Tanzania opposed to the idea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
