<HEADLINE> Jordanian Parliament Condemns U.S. Missile Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's Lower House of
Parliament fiercely denounced on Saturday the Thursday missile
attacks by the United States in Sudan and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. missile attacks were "an aggression on the
sovereignty and territorial integrity" of these two countries
"under the pretext of pursuing terrorism," the house said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Such aggression also represented "a deliberate provocation of
the peoples' rights," the house added in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. launched the attacks on a number of suspected
terrorist-related sites in Afghanistan and Sudan Thursday in
retaliation against the bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Lower House said the best way to fight terrorism
is through international cooperation and peaceful and diplomatic
methods.
</P>
<P>
The nationalist-dominated Lower House often adopts hard
policies against Israel and the United States.
</P>
<P>
In contrast with the Lower House's statement, Jordan's Royal
Court and government were relatively mild while commenting on
this issue. They did not criticize the U.S. missile attacks, but
instead condemned terrorism in general.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has declared Jordan as its third para-allied country
in the Middle East after Israel and Egypt. Its economic and
military aid for Jordan reached 225 million U.S. dollars in
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
