<HEADLINE> Sudan Urges U.N. Security Council Meeting on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Sudan Saturday asked the U.N.
Security Council to hold an urgent meeting on the recent U.S. air
raid on an alleged terrorist-related site in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the Security Council, the Sudanese Ministry of
Foreign Relations asked the Security Council to shoulder its
responsibility under the U.N. Charter and condemn the
U.S. aggression, Sudanese News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., accusing Sudan of sponsoring international terrorism,
fired cruise missiles Thursday night at a pharmaceutical factory
in Khartoum in what it claimed retaliation for the twin bombings
of its embassies in Kenya and Tanzania on August 7.
</P>
<P>
More than 250 people were killed and 5,000 others wounded in
the bombings.
</P>
<P>
In the message, Sudan requested that the United Nations set up
a technical fact-finding committee to probe the claims of the
United States and adopt measures to prevent the repetition of
similar strikes in the future.
</P>
<P>
Such actions are "grave behavior and flagrant violation of the
U.N. Charter," said the message.
</P>
<P>
The ministry pointed out that the U.S. moves are aimed at
defaming Sudan and undermining its relations with other countries.
</P>
<P>
In the message, Sudan held the United States responsible for
all the human and material losses resulting from the aggression,
asserting its readiness to provide all relevant information on the
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Sudan does not attack or threaten the U.S. interests on the
basis of principle of Islam and humanity and is ready for full
cooperation in tracking down the perpetrators of the bombings of
the two U.S. embassies, the foreign ministry said in the message.
</P>
</TEXT>
