<HEADLINE> Six Taiwan Residents Killed In Bus Accident In Gansu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Seven people, 6 of them tourists
from Taiwan, were killed Saturday, when the bus they were riding
in was involved in a head-on collision with a truck in the city of
Jiuquan in northwest China's Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
The accident occured at 4:30 p.m. The bus, which belonged to
China International Travel Service's Jiuquan Branch, was carrying
17 people, 14 of them Taiwanese. The bus driver and 5 of the
Taiwan residents were killed instantly and another Taiwan resident
died later.
</P>
<P>
The 6 Taiwan residents, 5 men and 1 woman, were in their 60s or
70s. One Taiwan resident who was seriously injured was
hospitalized but is now out of danger.
</P>
<P>
The injured were taken to a hospital in the city of Yumen for
emergency care and were moved to another hospital on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Gansu provincial government is treating the matter very
seriously and officials from Beijing's Association for Relations
across the Taiwan Strait are expected to come to Gansu. Relatives
of the victims will come to Lanzhou, the provincial capital, or to
Jiuquan and Jiayuguan, as will travel agency officials.
</P>
<P>
The accident is still under investigation, but initial reports
are that it occurred when the truck crossed the medial strip into
the oncoming bus's path. But the high speed of both vehicles is
also believed to be a factor, local officials say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
