<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Situation Still Tense (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Flooding on the Yangtze has caused at least 200 billion yuan
(24.1 billion U.S. dollars) worth of damage. The disaster also
claimed thousands of lives and affected more than 240 million
people.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said today that at least 19 people died in
flooding caused by torrential rains in Sichuan Province, in the
Southwest, between August 19 and 21, and another three people were
reported missing.
</P>
<P>
More than 8.5 million people, or a quarter of the population of
Heilongjiang Province, have been affected by this year's
devastating floods, and agricultural losses are estimated at 14
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin has postponed a visit to Japan and Russia
because of the flooding. Li Peng, chairman of the National
People's Congress Standing Committee, spoke with leaders of the
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region on Saturday evening about the
flood situation there and to inquire about people involved in the
fight. Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, is still
inspecting the flood situation in Jiangxi and Hunan provinces.
</P>
<P>
By Wednesday, the State Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters had sent 200 million yuan worth of goods to areas
along the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze, Nenjiang and
Songhua.
</P>
<P>
More than 2.7 billion yuan worth of donations had been sent to
China's Ministry of Civil Affairs, the Red Cross Society of China,
and the All-China Charity Federation by Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
The eight non-communist parties and the All-China Federation of
Industry and Commerce have contributed 613,900 yuan. A few days
ago, blankets, tents, and water purifiers donated by the United
States government were sent to Hunan by air. China Daily reports
that the People's Insurance Company of China group (PICC) had paid
1 billion yuan for damage in flood-hit areas by August 20.
</P>
<P>
Flood-stricken areas are expecting more cotton quilts, drinking
water, drugs, and other items.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980823.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Situation Still Tense (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Floods are often accompanied by epidemic diseases, and Health
Minister Zhang Wenkang says that the disease situation in China's
flooded areas is under control but that infectious diseases are
still a threat.
</P>
<P>
About 400 cases of snail fever have been reported in Hubei,
Hunan, Jiangxi, Anhui and Jiangsu provinces, where the worst
flooding has taken place, and more cases are expected in the near
future because snail fever takes a fairly long time, about 40
days, to develop.
</P>
<P>
The Minister said that the incidence of intestinal disease,
dysentery, hepatitis, and colds is greater than for the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
A large number of medical teams are working day and night to
treat the sick.
</P>
<P>
China said today that it would stop the cutting of timber in
the western part of Sichuan on the upper reaches of the Yangtze to
stop the soil erosion there that has made the flooding worse.
</P>
<P>
The felling of trees on 4.63 million hectares of Chuanxi Forest
Area land will cease and lumber sellers there will be closed down,
without exception, on September 1, Sichuan's Governor Song Baorui
told Xinhua. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
