<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Dhaka-Delhi Relations May Deteriorate Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh and India are at a row
over the so-called "illegal Bangladeshi nationals" in India, which
analysts said might undermine relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A report in Sunday's edition of the national English-language
newspaper, The Independent, said that the Indian government has
decided to formulate a "national policy on infiltration, and
identification and deportation of Bangladeshi nationals" living in
India illegally.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government convened on Monday a meeting of officials
of the states of West Bengal and Maharashtra on the deportation
issue, a signal showing that India would take a "tough decision to
end 'infiltration,'" the report said.
</P>
<P>
And in West Bengal, the issue of push-back of alleged
Bangladeshi nationals has come full circle, following an official
pronouncement by the West Bengal government to extradite 46
Bengali-speaking people, allegedly Bangladeshis, a volte-face of
its original stance over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the West Bengal government held that among the
would-be Bengali-speaking deportees from the southwestern Indian
state of Maharashtra there were a large number of Indians
belonging to West Bengal state, strongly protesting against the
proposed deportation of so-called Bangladeshis.
</P>
<P>
In-built compulsions within the state compelled the government
to shift its position on the issue of deportation of
"Bangladeshis," allegedly living in Maharashtra and other states
of India, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The issue of deporting Bengali-speaking people in Maharashtra
was raised in India's parliament last month by Home Minister Lal
Krishna Advani, and was strongly opposed by West Bengal. West
Bengal Chief Minister Jyoti Basu said that his state would be
heavily affected if Bengali-speaking nationals were overthrown
from Bombay and Maharashtra, a commentary in the newspaper The New
Nation daily said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
India's "push-back" issue was first raised in 1993 by the then
Indian Congress government and died down when Bangladesh applied
force by deploying security forces to resist such moves, and
nothing was heard from India since then, the commentary said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, a report in The Independent daily said that
Bangladesh would not accept anybody pushed into its territory "in
the name of push-back," as "no Bangladeshi is staying in India
illegally," quoting a source of an inter-ministerial meeting
presided over by Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad, which
discussed the latest situation arising out of the "push-back" of
so-called Bangladeshis by India.
</P>
<P>
"We are not going to accept them as Bangladeshi -- if they (the
Indian authorities) suspect anybody as Bangladeshi, they have to
follow internationally accepted norms and procedure for
repatriation," as "push-back is not a legal procedure," the report
quoted the source as saying.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing on August 13, the foreign minister said
that there were no illegal Bangladeshi nationals living in India
and so there was no question of repatriating Bangladeshis from
India. He urged India not to take any unilateral decision on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the present Indian government would
not do anything that would jeopardize the "excellent relations"
existing between the two countries. "We hope that they would
continue with the relations of cooperation, friendship and
understanding between India and Bangladesh," he said.
</P>
<P>
And at a press conference early this month, Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina also denied that there were any illegal Bangladeshis
in India.
</P>
<P>
The dispute over the so-called "illegal Bangladeshis" in India
between the two neighbors would inevitably have a negative impact
on their relations, whatever the motives behind the moves of the
Indians, according to the analysts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980823.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Intensifies Search for Missing Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 23 (Xinhua) -- As bad weather blocked
