morning, Nepal intensified the ground efforts on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
As it was raining and cloudy on top of the mountains and
jungles, the search operation by the four helicopters were
interrupted time and again, a duty officer at the Rescue and
Coordination Center (RCC) of the capital's Tribhuvan International
Airport told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Tourism and Civil Aviation Ananda Prasad Dhungana
told the Lower House of Parliament Sunday that the ground
operation has been intensified.
</P>
<P>
He said that the area has been determined and a strategy has
been worked out for continuing vigorously the search and rescue
operation.
</P>
<P>
The twin Otter plane with 18 people on board including three
crew members and three Indians lost contact five minutes after it
took off at 11:10 am Friday in Jomsom, western Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated plane which belongs to the private-owned Lumbini
Airways was scheduled to arrive in Pokhara, 80 kilometres away, at
11:30.
</P>
<P>
The army and police are joining in the search operation
together with local people.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Search and Rescue Organization had been requested to
help track the plane through satellite, but the duty officer at
RCC said that the longitude and latitude determined by the Indian
side is not an area lying on the route.
</P>
<P>
Minister Dhungana said that airports in New Delhi, Calcutta,
Patna and Bangalore of India had been contacted, but no
significant information was available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
