<DOCNO> XIE19980823.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe Snubs Mandela's Mediation Efforts on Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 23 (Xinhua) -- An emergency southern African
summit on the crisis in Democratic Republic of congo (DRC) called
for by South African President Nelson Mandela got underway Sunday
afternoon in Pretoria despite the absence of Zimbabwean President
Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's presidential spokesman George Charamba told the
country's news agency ZIANA Sunday that Mugabe was not going to
attend the talks called by Mandela, chairman of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC), to broker a ceasefire in
the DRC which is facing a rebellion from Tutsis-led soldiers.
</P>
<P>
"The SADC met and took a decision through its defense
ministers last week in Harare and that decision is being
implemented so we cannot go back on that decision to see whether
it is proper for the region to deploy troops in the DRC,"
Charamba said.
</P>
<P>
"The definite answer is that we are not going to attend the
summit," he added.
</P>
<P>
Nine SADC defense ministers met here last Tuesday and agreed
that the region should intervene in the DRC crisis militarily and
Zimbabwean troops numbering over 600 have been reportedly
deployed alongside Congolese troops in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's spokesman Parks Mankahlana, however, told
journalists in South Africa that efforts to get Angolan President
Eduardo dos Santos and Mugabe to the twin summit which began
Saturday were still underway.
</P>
<P>
Already in Pretoria for the talks are Rwandan President
Pasteur Bizimungu, Uganda's Yoweri Museveni, and representatives
sent in by DRC President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Dos Santos has, like Kabila, claimed illness saying he will
send a representative.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe and Mandela have differences over the running of the
regional organ on politics, defense and security which Mandela
thinks should fall under SADC structures, which he currently
chairs.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also differed on how best to deal with the DRC
crisis with Mandela favoring a diplomatic solution whereas
Mugabe, who chairs the security organ has steadfastly defended
the military option.
</P>
<P>
A Tutsi-led rebellion against Kabila's regime began in the DRC
on August 2. The rebels claimed Sunday to have occupied the city
Kisangani, the third largest city in the vast central African
country, as well as the strategic airport of Kitona in the
southwest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
