<HEADLINE> Floodwater Levels Down, But Flood Situation Still Tense (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The floodwaters gradually
receded on the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River and
on the Songhua River today, but the fight continues.
</P>
<P>
Problems often appear when the flood begins to ebb, especially
when the embankments have been soaked for more than 50 days on the
Yangtze, according to one State Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters official.
</P>
<P>
The official told Xinhua this afternoon that the water level in
Hubei dropped to 43.67 meters at Shashi and 29.25 meters at
Hankou, and to 22.42 meters at Jiujiang in Jiangxi by 2:00
p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
The water level on Dongting Lake at Chenglingji went down 0.15
meter to 35.7 meters, while that on Poyang Lake it fell by 0.03
meters to 21.84 meters.
</P>
<P>
The number of leaks and dike breaks have increased near
Jingjiang at the narrowest part of the Yangtze, in spite of the
receding floodwaters, according to evening reports from China
Central Television.
</P>
<P>
In the Northeast, water levels on the Nenjiang and Songhua
rivers were down a bit upstream from Harbin but continued to rise
downstream. The Songhua at Harbin was still at 120.89 meters which
it reached on Saturday noon, 0.84 meter higher than the previous
record.
</P>
</TEXT>
