<HEADLINE> China's Public Security Ministry Says Flood Areas Need Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 23 (Xinhua) -- China's Public Security Ministry
told Public Security bureaus in flooded areas today that acts of
theft and robbery need to be punished severely.
</P>
<P>
Public Security bureaus in central China's Hunan Province have
sent 4,900 police to stop people from taking sand from the Yangtze
River and have confiscated 519 boats used for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
Patrols have been increased in Hunan's Anxiang County to cope
with the increased number of break-ins. They caught 8 gangs and 63
suspects over a five-day period.
</P>
<P>
Near the city of Jiujiang, a truck carrying relief materials
was intercepted in Xingzi County, but local police caught the
people the same night.
</P>
<P>
The Public Security Bureau of Taoyang County in Jilin Province
caught a gang that was breaking into houses while the owners were
busy fighting floods.
</P>
<P>
Police in the city of Qiqihar took only 7 minutes to arrest 3
armed men who were suspected of stealing waterproof boots.
</P>
<P>
In western Jilin Province, order has been maintained since the
flooding began, and the number of serious crimes in the past two
months has dropped by as much as 90 percent from the same period
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Traffic police have had to deal with 27,000
traffic jams, straighten up more than 5,000 traffic signs,
establish 1,500 traffic safety facilities, and safeguard 1,500
relief motorcades since the flooding began. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
