<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia, Pacific Regional Conference on Rehabilitation Opens in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,500
representatives from various countries and regions in the world
attended the 11th Rehabilitation International Asia and the
Pacific Regional Conference which was opened here Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The conference aims at maintaining a complementary balance
between the East and the West, the tradition and the modern, and
presenting both historical perspectives and new trends of the
rehabilitation for the disabled people, said Harry Fang,
chairperson of the Joint Council for the Physically and Mentally
Disabled at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
A message from Chinese President Jiang Zemin was read by Deng
Pufang, president of the China Disabled Persons' Federation, at
the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
In the message, Jiang extended his warm congratulations to the
conference on behalf of the Chinese government and people as well
as in his own name.
</P>
<P>
He said that disability exists along with human beings. People
with disabilities have the desire and ability to participate in
community life and are equally creators of social wealth for which
 they make much greater efforts than people without disabilities.
</P>
<P>
They, as all others, should be entitled to all human dignity
and rights. The emancipation of disabled people as the most
under-privileged group in the society symbolizes significantly the
 development of human civilization and social progress, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang noted that the 48th Session of the UNESCAP (United
Nations Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific)
held in Beijing in April, 1992 adopted unanimously a resolution,
proclaiming 1993-2002 as the Asian and Pacific Decade of Disabled
Persons.
</P>
<P>
Such an effort and that of Rehabilitation International for
improving rehabilitation service to disabled people expresses the
lofty pursuit of the international community for further improving
 the status of disabled people and giving more play to their roles
 in society. The convening of this conference will make new
contribution to the promotion of the undertaking of disabled
people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that China takes a considerable portion in the world
 population with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government and people are willing to work together
 with the international community and share our efforts for
realizing the goals of 'equality, participating and sharing' of
disabled people and for our endeavor of human civilization and
progress," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR), said at the opening ceremony: "we
have been making great strides in developing rehabilitation
services, promoting awareness and understanding, and moving
towards our shared goal of equal opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"Our achievements are results of the joint efforts of
government departments, statutory bodies and non-governmental
organizations including self-help organizations. We will enhance
these partnerships and pursue together the goals set out in our
White Paper on Rehabilitation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tung stressed that the needs of people with disabilities should
 not be neglected under the present economic climate and he
expressed the hope that the conference would build on the progress
 made and contribute to the well being of people with disability
by promoting regional cooperation and support.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Deng Pufang said that over the past decade, 3
million disabled people in China received various rehabilitation
service, school enrollment rate of disabled children increased
from under 20 percent up to 64 percent, 2 million disabled people
received vocational training, and employment rate of disabled
persons increased from 50 percent up to 72 percent.
</P>
<P>
Through poverty alleviation projects, 5 million poor disabled
people in rural areas have been helped out of poverty, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the opening ceremony, both Tung Chee Hwa and Steward
Chau Cham Son, respectively on behalf of the HKSAR government and
the Hong Kong Jockey Club, received the presentation of Ri Life
Patrons from Rehabilitation International by president Dr. Arthur
O'Reilly.
</P>
<P>
Adrianus Mooy, under secretary general of the United Nations
Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific, made a
keynote speech entitled "The Asian and Pacific Decade of Disabled
Persons". Administrative Secretary Anson Chan and other
high-ranking SAR officials and representatives from the
rehabilitation sector of the Chinese mainland participated in the
opening ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
