<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weizman: Peace Process Must Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman
said Sunday that the Middle East peace process must continue
despite the killing of Rabbi Shlomo Raanan, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
Weizman said this while in a condolence call at Raanan's
family. The 63-year-old rabbi was stabbed to death in his home
Thursday night by a Palestinian intruder in Tel Rumeida, Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Following the incident, Israel security forces imposed a curfew
in the city forbidding the Palestinians leaving and entering,
particularly in the city sector under their control.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, some local Jewish settler's leaders
criticized Weizman for his support to the peace process, saying
he is a "spy" for the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"For my whole life I have fought for the security and benefit of
Israel and no body can expressed his doubt about that," Weizman
said, rejecting the criticism.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his sorrow for the killing of the rabbi, but said
that Israel could live in complete peace only after reaching an
peace agreement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The killing of Raanan caused great concern in Israel. Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said he has contacted Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat, demanding the assailant, believed to have
fled to the Palestinian-controlled sector of Hebron, be arrested.
</P>
<P>
He said the killing reinforced his resolve not to sign a deal
on a troop withdrawal from the West Bank unless the Palestinians
guarantee they will meet their security obligations.
</P>
<P>
Israeli cabinet members discussed this issue at the weekly
meeting on Sunday and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai said
preventive security measures must be taken to ensure the safety of
Jewish settlers in the city.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security forces maintained a high profile in Hebron
over the weekend, as a tense calm prevailed. The Palestinian
security forces are also investigating the incident, but the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) did not condemn the killing.
</P>
<P>
"It is essential that the PNA leaders openly condemn the
killing incident and they must take strict measures to ensure that
such incident will not happen again," Weizman said during the
visit.
</P>
<P>
About 400 Jewish settlers are living in Hebron, a city with a
30,000 Palestinian population, and only seven Jewish families
living in Tel Rumeida.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Labor Party Chairman Ehud Barak rejected on Sunday the
Hebron Jewish settler leader's criticism about Weizman, saying
they must be brought to court for their treatment of the president.
</P>
<P>
He said that Weizman is a key peace maker in the region and
respected by not only the Israeli people, but the people of all
countries in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
