<HEADLINE> Epidemic Disease Prevention In China's Flood Areas (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 23 (Xinhua) -- After fighting floods, China's
flood-stricken areas have put the prevention of epidemic disease
at the top of their work list.
</P>
<P>
Many teams of doctors and disease prevention specialists from
Beijing and other big cities have been sent to flooded areas along
the Yangtze, Songhua and Nenjiang rivers in response to President
Jiang Zemin's demand that epidemic diseases be prevented in those
areas.
</P>
<P>
Sanitation workers have been distributing drugs to flood
victims in central China's Hunan Province and the provincial
government is focusing on providing disease prevention information
and watching food, drinking water, and environment conditions.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government warned of a possibility of epidemic
diseases because of worsening pollution. In Anxiang County, 41
local medical teams and six from other provinces are working on a
70-km dikes with a clinic every two km.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Health, over 1,500 cases of
intestinal diseases have been repored in seven province-level
areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980823.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Epidemic Disease Prevention  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The provincial government of Jilin, where there are more than
1.5 million flood victims, has a long-term disease prevention
program with more than 100 medical teams.
</P>
<P>
Ma Shenying, head of the Provincial Sanitation and Epidemic
Station, says that Jilin has a lot of difficulties because of the
more than 30,000 homeless people on a one-sq.km. strip of land.
</P>
<P>
The province has managed to keep flood victims with their
cattle and has built temporary lavatories and sterilized water.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin, a coastal city in northern China that has the task of
helping Heilongjiang Province, has sent six disease prevention
specialists to the province to help establish 30 provincial teams,
and sent 10 million yuan (1.2 billion U.S. dollars) worth of goods
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The city is also speeding up production of drugs and medical
equipment for the flood-stricken province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
