<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola, Zimbabwe Not to Attend SADC Summit: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's attempts to
bring a ceasefire in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC)
and heal a rift in the 14-member Southern African Development
Community (SADC) was being hampered Sunday due to the absence of
key players in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
"Neither Angola nor Zimbabwe will be involved at all in the
SADC summit," Parks Mankahlana, spokesman for South African
President Nelson Mandela, told reporters in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Mankahlana said they would not send delegations, but efforts
to get them to have peace negotiation in South Africa have not
stopped.
</P>
<P>
Both Zimbabwe and Angola are at the forefront of the SADC camp
favoring military intervention in the DRC and have sent troops
and arms to support President Laurent Kabila, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, attempts to broker peace between the DRC government
and Uganda and Rwanda, which are allegedly backing the rebels,
were also being frustrated.
</P>
<P>
A DRC delegation attending the talks hosted by Mandela was
consulting Kabila about a South African proposal for peace tabled
in Pretoria earlier.
</P>
<P>
The rival parties have yet to meet at the negotiating table
and South African leaders are shuffling between the two groups.
</P>
<P>
The peace proposal, if accepted by the DRC, Rwanda and Uganda,
will be tabled at the SADC summit.
</P>
<P>
The meeting later Sunday will also be attended by Kenya's
President Daniel arap Moi (who is not a member of the SADC) and a
representative of the Organization of African Unity, diplomatic
sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
