<HEADLINE> Nigerian Leader Leaves for S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian military leader General
Abdulsalam Abubakar will leave for Johannesburg Sunday for a
four-day state visit to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The visit, which is at the invitation of South African
President Nelson Mandela, would afford the two leaders the
opportunity to discuss bilateral and multi-lateral issues
particularly as it concerns peace and stability in Africa, the
official New Nigerian newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the South African Foreign Ministry said Nigeria's
transition to democratic civil rule would top the agenda of talks
between Abubakar and Mandela.
</P>
<P>
The visit to South Africa would be Abubakar's first trip
abroad since he came to power on June 9.
</P>
<P>
It is also the first visit by a Nigerian leader to
Johannesburg since 1995, when bilateral relations got strained as
Mandela led the call for international sanctions against Nigeria
for executing nine minority activists.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic ice between the two leading African nations began
to break after Abubakar assumed power in June and took moves to
promote democracy and human rights in the most populous African
country, including releasing all political detainees and starting
dialog with opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
South African Vice-President Thabo Mbeki visited Nigeria in
July in the height of the political crisis in Nigeria, following
the death in detention of Moshood Abiola, the believed winner of
the annulled 1993 presidential election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
