<HEADLINE> Zambia's Chambishi Plants Sold for $50 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's Chambishi cobalt and
acid plants have been sold to Avmin of South Africa at 50 million
U.S. Dollars, raising optimism for a higher price for Nkana and
Nchanga divisions of the country's two largest copper mines.
</P>
<P>
The deal is expected to be sealed within next week, Times of
Zambia said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the negotiating team in charge of privatizing
the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) said prospects of
selling Nkana and Nchanga divisions at a higher price were high,
considering the sum of 150 million Dollars offered by the
collapsed Kafue Consortium, a trans-national corporation, to the
two mines together with the Chambishi cobalt and acid plants.
</P>
<P>
The coming back of Avmin, one of the major companies in the
Kafue Consortium which intended to buy the Nkana and Nchanga
mines last year and later gave up following its collapse, has
raised much excitement and hope that other companies would join
the race to bid for the remaining ZCCM divisions individually.
</P>
<P>
Avmin, according to the paper, will construct a new processing
facility for the slug material which will be commissioned in 30
months' time. And the workers in the Chambishi components will
be transferred to the company.
</P>
<P>
The Nkana and Nchanga mines register over 60 percent of ZCCM's
copper output. Their privatization is a precondition set by the
Paris Club to release its 530 million Dollars of pledged aid to
Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
