<DOCNO> XIE19980823.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Launch National Malaria Mobilization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Health Minister
Adem Ibrahim has announced that a national malaria social
mobilization week will be launched from August 24 to 30 to
enhance public awareness on the disease.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian Herald, Adem told a press
conference Saturday though the government has been in the past
supporting efforts to bring malaria under control, the
participation of non-governmental and other sectors was less than
expected.
</P>
<P>
The lukewarm to the fight against malaria was due to lack of
public awareness about the challenge and lack of information on
the systematic approach to contain the spread of the epidemic, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 300 to 500 million people who suffer from malaria and
the more than two million who die of malaria in the world
annually, 90 percent are Africans, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
In Ethiopia, where two-thirds of the population is affected by
malaria, the disease is "unstable" due to the environment which
worsens the situation than in the other sub-Saharan countries,
Ibrahim added.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the mobilization week will be observed by
conducting malaria prevention activities and providing education
on the prevention and control of the disease in all regional
states.
</P>
<P>
The objectives of the malaria week are to inform the public
about the socio-economic effects of the disease and the measures
to be taken to control it as well as enhance the role of
governmental, non-governmental organizations and the public at
large in efforts being undertaken in its prevention and control.
</P>
<P>
The prevention and control of malaria is one of priority tasks
indicated in the government's health policy, he said, adding that
malaria control will be the major duty of health institutions
followed by implementing health management strategy in the coming
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
