<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flooding in Inner Mongolia Basically under Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Major flood bursts and danger
spots in the eastern part of north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region have basically been brought under control to
date, local officials told Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
While most flood-stranded victims have been evacuated, flood
control workers and soldiers are consolidating dykes and
embankments to prepare for possible new floods, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia suffered severe flooding since July, with bursts
and mud-rock flows spotted frequently along more than 20 rivers in
the region's eastern part.
</P>
<P>
Local people and soldiers have worked hard for the past month
to fight the floods. The Beijing Military Area Command and the
Shenyang Military Area Command have sent more than five thousand
soldiers and six helicopters to join in the anti-flood work.
</P>
<P>
So far, most of the 813 bursts have been plugged and some 42
kilometres of embankments have been consolidated.
</P>
<P>
While more than 900,000 flood victims have been evacuated to
safe places, about 10,000 people still besieged by floods have got
out of danger and have food, medicines and daily necessities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
