<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Manpower and Immigration Ahmed
el-Amawi has said that 29,000 job opportunities were provided to
Egyptians by Arab countries in the first quarter of this year, the
Egyptian Gazette daily reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
El-Amawi told reporters on Saturday that the job opportunities
were secured due to agreements on the labor field reached between
Egypt and the Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Undersecretary of State for Labor Hosni Al Anani said
the job opportunities were mainly provided by Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Turkey are holding talks on a natural gas
deal, Egypt's Alam Al Yom daily reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is considering importing 5 billion cubic meters of gas
annually through pipelines in the Mediterranean, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The projected gas deal is expected to further augment the trade
volume between the two countries, which stood at 695 million U.S.
dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Indian Minister of Textiles Ram Rana said that Egypt
has become India's biggest trade partner in Africa and Middle
East, the Egyptian Al-Ahram daily reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Rana told reporters at the end of his four-day visit to Egypt
on Saturday that the trade volume between the two countries rose
to 500 million dollars in 1997 from 200 million dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
He said that Egypt exports mainly oil, cotton, fertilizers,
metals and chemicals to India while its imports from India include
textiles, medicine and agricultural machines.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan exported 70 percent of the medicines
manufactured by 14 pharmaceutical companies in the past years, the
semi-official Jordan Times daily reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's medicines were mostly sold to Iraq under the 1996
United Nations oil-for-food program, which allows Iraq to sell a
limited amount of oil to buy humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
Jordan produces some 140 million dollars worth of medicines
every year. 
</P>
