<HEADLINE> Iranian Speaker Condemns U.S. Attacks on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Majlis (Parliament)
Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri Sunday condemned the recent United
States air raids on Sudan and Afghanistan as proof of
state-sponsored terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Majlis, Nateq-Nouri said the strikes were clear
examples of terrorist acts conducted by a government despite a
pretext that they were launched to combat terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. launched surprise air attacks Thursday night against
six sites in Afghanistan and a pharmaceutical factory in Sudan,
which Washington described as key bases used by terrorists behind
the August 7 bombings of U.S. embassies in capitals of Kenya and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
There is no guarantee that Washington will not attack any
other country, Nateq-Nouri said.
</P>
<P>
He said that it was the law of jungle that Washington allows
itself to violate international norms and regulations and attack
any country it chooses.
</P>
<P>
Whenever the U.S. administration faces a domestic problem, it
tries to divert the public attention, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that at this time, the objective was to shift the
attention away from the sex scandal involving U.S. President Bill
Clinton who admitted last week that he had an inappropriate
relationship with a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
Despite the repeated U.S. accusations against Iran of
harboring and supporting terrorism, Nateq-Nouri said that Iran
deplores terrorism, state terrorism in particular, because it is
also a victim of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami Saturday condemned the U.S.
missile attacks and voiced support for Khartoum to lodge complain
to the United Nations against Washington.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with his Sudanese counterpart Omar
Hassan al-Bashir, Khatami termed the U.S. attack as an aggression
against Sudan, violation of international laws and threat to the
world security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
