<HEADLINE> Micronesia to Host SPF Heads of Government Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The annual South Pacific
Forum (SPF) heads of government meeting is scheduled to begin
Monday in Pohnpei, capital of the Federated States of Micronesia.
</P>
<P>
Issues expected to be discussed at the two-day meeting of the
heads of government of SPF's 16 member countries include trade
liberalization and economic reforms, the impact of the Asian
financial crisis on the Pacific region, climate change, regional
security, nuclear testing and management of fisheries.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, prime ministers of New Zealand,
Australia, Papua New Guinea and Samoa will be unable to attend the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
It is believed to be the first time both the Australian and New
 Zealand prime ministers are absent from the forum.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard, grappling with
Australia's tax reforms and an imminent election, will be
represented at the forum by Foreign Minister Alexander Downer.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley announced in a
statement a few days ago that Foreign Minister Don McKinnon would
represent New Zealand on her behalf at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Shipley said she was disappointed that she was unable to meet
Pacific leaders, because of the "domestic political situation."
</P>
<P>
It is reported that New Zealand and Australia will use the
forum in Pohnpei to seek support for a South Pacific whale
sanctuary, to complement existing sanctuaries in the Southern and
Indian Oceans. Under the plan, the entire southern hemisphere
could become a whale sanctuary.
</P>
</TEXT>
