<HEADLINE> Pak Minister Leaves for Iran, Central Asian Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Minister of State
for Foreign Affairs Siddique Khan Kanju left here Sunday for a
four-day visit to Iran and three Central Asian countries for talks
mainly focusing on Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The first stop of Kanju's four-day tour will be Tehran, where
he is scheduled to have wide-ranging exchange of views with the
Iranian leaders, according to a statement by Kanju before his
departure.
</P>
<P>
After his visit to Iran, Kanju is also to visit Uzbekistan,
Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
Besides bilateral matters, the Afghan issue will prominently
figure in the talks with leaders of Iran and the three Central
Asian countries, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Central Asian countries have expressed serious concern
over the Taliban militia's recent victories in northern
Afghanistan and some of them accused Pakistan of backing the
Taliban. However, the charges have been denied by Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"Iran is our close and fraternal neighbor and we always consult
each other on such occasion," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
In the Central Asian states, Kanju is to apprise their
leadership of Pakistan's assessment of the situation in
Afghanistan and the ways of ensuring regional peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
"Our discussions would also focus on bilateral relations with
Tajikistan, Uzbekistan and Turkmenistan, which are based on
historical bonds of faith and kinship," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Kanju said he was looking forward to "very constructive
exchange of views during the visit to these brotherly countries"
and was hopeful of "a positive outcome." 
</P>
