<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Stops Lumbering of Natural Forests in Western Sichuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, August 23 (Xinhua) -- China announced today to stop
lumbering of natural forests in the western part of Sichuan
Province on the upper reaches of the Yangtze River in a bid to
curb severe soil erosion that exacerbates the threat of floods.
</P>
<P>
Felling of natural trees in the Chuanxi Forest Area, totaling
4.63 million hectares, will be prohibited and wood markets there
will be closed down without any exception from September 1, Song
Baorui, provincial governor, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The decision made by the provincial government will greatly
help protect forest resources and improve ecological balance on
the upper reaches of the Yangtze River, Song said.
</P>
<P>
Such a move comes at a time when devastating Yangtze floods
have caused hundreds of billion yuan economic losses and claimed
thousands of lives so far this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the governor, a total of 54 counties in the
western part of Sichuan, one of the most densely-populated
provinces in southwest China, are subject to the unconditioned
prohibition order.
</P>
<P>
The Chuanxi Forest Area, one of the three largest forest areas
in China, has a major role in conserving headwaters of the Yangtze
River. But excessive felling has remarkably weakened its role.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that more than 70 lumbering firms have
been operating in the area and sold some 120 million cubic metres
of wood out of the area for the past decades.
</P>
<P>
As a result of reduction in natural forests and ecological
imbalance, the area of soil erosion in the western part of Sichuan
has almost doubled from 60,000 square kilometres in the 1950s to
110,000 square kilometres at present.
</P>
<P>
"For the sake of both local environment and all the Yangtze
areas, we now have to act promptly to protect the natural forests
and curb soil erosion," said Xie Shijie, secretary of the Sichuan
Provincial Committee of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
According to a comprehensive afforestation program of the
province, strict protection will be exercised in the Chuanxi
Forest Area upon the ceasing of lumbering, while forest
regeneration will be conducted in another 1.83 million hectares of
land between 1998 and 2010.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some 8.97 million hectares of hillsides will be
closed to livestock grazing and fuel gathering so as to facilitate
afforestation. Workers of the current lumbering firms will be
responsible for planting and protecting trees.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2010, the Chuanxi Forest Area will be capable of
conserving 39 billion cubic metres of headwaters and soil erosion
in the area will be basically under control, thus greatly reducing
the danger caused by Yangtze floods, Song said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
