<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Papers Circulated on Secession of Zambia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Seditious materials on the
status of Zambia's Western Province have surfaced in the capital
city of Lusaka, prompting the government warning to deal with
those distributing them ruthlessly.
</P>
<P>
The brochures printed on high quality papers are being
circulated by a group calling itself the Barotse Patriotic Front
on Self-Determination (BPF), government-owned Times of Zambia
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
BPF is distributing brochures justifying continued secession
claims by proponents of the dead Barotseland Agreement signed
between the government of the former ruling United National
Independence Party (UNIP) and the Litunga (general chief) of
Western Province in 1964 when Zambia won its independence from
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Western Province, which was called Barotseland, enjoyed half
independence under British colonial rule and strived to become an
independent country before it became part of Zambia in 1964 and
in 1969 got its present name.
</P>
<P>
The seditious papers which demand independence of the Western
Province from the central government contained the proposed
national anthem and constitution of Barotseland, according to the
paper.
</P>
<P>
BPF alleges despite the fact that Barotseland joined Zambia
through a trade-off over its government and resources, the
des-empowering and deliberate impoverishment of Barotseland could
not be allowed to continue.
</P>
<P>
In response to the seditious propaganda, Home Affairs Minister
Peter Machungwa warned in Lusaka Saturday that those breaking the
law will be dealt with in accordance with the law of the land.
</P>
<P>
Times newspaper quoted him as saying that it is a "very
serious matter that calls for thorough study".
</P>
<P>
Richard Sakala, press and public relations assistant at the
State House, described the materials contained in the brochures
as "seditious" and "treasonable".
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Beenwell Chimfwembe said authenticity of the
claims contained in the brochures would be investigated and
"appropriate" action could be taken.
</P>
<P>
In the brochures being circulated, BPF alleges that the
Zambian government has stifled the people of Barotseland of their
democratic right for a long time and that time had come to
correct the situation.
</P>
<P>
Because Barotseland voluntarily entered into the agreement to
join in Zambia several decades ago, it was only logical for it to
voluntarily divorce itself now from the agreement and revert to
its original status, claimed BPF.
</P>
<P>
"It is certain that the recognition of Barotseland's inherent
right to self-government is overdue and not an attempt to rewrite
the past but to build a better future for all its people," reads
one of the brochures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
