<HEADLINE> Strong Quake Shakes Northern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- A strong earthquake measuring 6.1
on the Richter Scale hit the northern Philippines early Sunday
afternoon, the Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology
said.
</P>
<P>
The institute said in a press release that the jolt's epicenter
was 20 kilometers offshore and some 51 kilometers southwest of
Olongapo city in Bataan province.
</P>
<P>
The tremor, which struck at about 1:36 p.m. and lasted for
nearly one minute, was clearly felt in a number of cities in the
northern Philippines. Some residents in Manila said they felt
their houses shaking.
</P>
<P>
The institute said the quake was of tectonic origin and that
damage and aftershocks are expected. 
</P>
