<HEADLINE> Malaysia Stands for Convening Special UN Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia said Sunday it was
appropriate for a special session of the United Nations Security
Council to be convened as attention should be drawn to vital
issues related to the question of terrorism and the issue of the
U.S. action in violating the sovereignty of another country.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said this
after launching his ministry's Family Day in Kepong near here on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. launched missile strikes on Sudan and Afghanistan last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"This issue involves a principle which is most crucial and
which should not be ignored," the foreign minister told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating Malaysia's regret over the U.S. action, Abdullah
said that launching missile attacks on targets in Sudan or in any
other country was not the way to overcome the problem of
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly the U.S. action violated the sovereignty of that
independent nation which is also a member of the United Nations,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said that based on reports he had received, efforts
were underway for a special session to be convened.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the U.S. stand that it was striking back
following the bombing of the U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania,
Abdullah said that as far as he knew, the UN had not given its
blessings.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said that the support from the U.S. allies was
expected but still such missile attacks should not be resorted to
as it would not overcome the problem of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"We are also against terrorism and we condemn all forms of
terrorism," he said, adding Malaysia was concerned that the
missile strikes by the U.S. would further trigger terrorist
activities which would have far worse consequences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
