<HEADLINE> Congo (K) Rival Negotiators Still to Face Each </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Negotiators for a
ceasefire in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) have yet
to meet face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
Talks entered the second day in Pretoria Sunday with South
African leaders shuttling between the opposing camps, South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The mini-summit involving a representative of DRC President
Laurent Kabila and the presidents of Uganda and Rwanda began
Saturday night after the DRC representative arrived more than six
hours late.
</P>
<P>
The rival parties did not meet face-to-face, but exchanged
notes instead in a brief session.
</P>
<P>
Before the arrival of DRC Justice Minister Mwenze Kongolo,
Kabila's representative, Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and
his Rwandan counterpart Pasteur Bizimungu held talks with Mandela
and his deputy, Thabo Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
South African Defense Minister Joe Modise, Foreign Minister
Alfred Nzo and his deputy Aziz Pahad were also present.
</P>
<P>
Although Mandela's aide Parks Mankahlana denied that the
presidents of Uganda and Rwanda were miffed at being snubbed by
Kabila, it is understood the arrival of a junior DRC negotiator
has produced a protocol nightmare.
</P>
<P>
Kabila told Mandela by phone Saturday that he was unable to
attend as his doctor had ordered him to rest.
</P>
<P>
However, it is understood that Kabila wants Uganda and Rwanda,
which he blames for supporting the rebel invasion in the DRC, to
call a ceasefire first, before he will negotiate, said SAPA.
</P>
<P>
It could not be confirmed whether Kabila had been persuaded to
arrive for the talks Sunday, which will be followed by an
emergency summit of the 14-member Southern African Development
Community (SADC), which is split on how to deal with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
An official at Waterkloof air base told SAPA a plane from the
DRC was scheduled to land later in the day, but it could not be
confirmed immediately whether Kabila would be on board.
</P>
<P>
Twelve planes were expected to land during the morning, two of
which had already arrived.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, who heads the SADC faction
in favor of military intervention, will not attend the summit.
Nor will Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos, whose troops
are backing Kabila along with Zimbabwe, be present. Dos Santos is
reportedly ill and will send a representative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
