<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Zimbabweans Support Intervention in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabweans from all walks of
life have expressed their support for the country's joint
military intervention in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
In a snap survey conducted by the Sunday Mail, most citizens
applauded President Robert Mugabe's initiative as chairman of the
organ on politics, defense and security of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC), to send troops to the DRC together
with Angola, Zambia, Namibia and Tanzania as part of the efforts
to help DRC President Laurent Kabila fight against rebels trying
to overthrow him.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean troops currently in the DRC have been strategically
deployed around Kinshasa, the DRC capital, to secure the capital
from rebel advances.
</P>
<P>
Business leaders, political commentators and politicians
interviewed Saturday expressed support for the Zimbabwean
initiative.
</P>
<P>
"The continuous invasion by a group of people with
expansionist plans should stop. There ought to be a point when
leadership in the region has to rise and put a stop to this type
of destabilization," said Ben Mucheche, president of Indigenous
Business Development Center.
</P>
<P>
Nhlanhla Masuku, president of Zimbabwe National Chamber of
Commerce, said there was no way Zimbabwe could be wrong judging
by the support given by the U.N. Security Council and other
regional bodies.
</P>
<P>
Member of Parliament Richard Shambambeva-Nyandoro said, "I
feel very strongly that as SADC countries, the first thing we
should do is have unity in protecting each other as a region. We
should do everything possible to see that there are no
infiltrators as has happened to Congo, not only at SADC level,
but also as member states of the Organisation of African Unity."
</P>
<P>
Political commentator and theater activist Ngugi Wa Mirii said
the whole of Zimbabwe should support the government's position.
"We need to settle the Congo (issue) once and for all," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that if African heads of state could not solve their
problems based on selfishness, the continent could experience
another Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Member of Parliament Lazarue Nzarayebani said, "The decision
to intervene militarily to assist in the restoration of law and
order, democracy and rule of law in the DRC is a very progressive
move."
</P>
<P>
However, independent MP Margaret Dongo said the decision by
Zimbabwe to intervene in the DRC was made without consulting
parliament and as such was a decision of the ruling Zimbabwe
African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF).
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean National Students' Union and opposition United
Parties also issued the statements condemning Mugabe's military
intervention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980823.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Submits 1999 Budget to Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada has finally submitted to Congress the proposed
579.5-billion-peso (13.5 billion U.S. dollars) national budget for
1999, presidential Spokesman Jerry Barican said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Barican said Estrada submitted the budget proposal Saturday
night to the members of the House of Representatives led by
Speaker Manny Villar during the dinner the President hosted.
</P>
<P>
Upon receiving the proposed budget, Speaker Villar said the
lower chamber of Congress will act on it expeditiously, Barican
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Estrada described the budget as "market-friendly
and pro-poor" because it intends to balance the need to stimulate
economic activities, the need to provide basic services and the
need to ensure the private sector of credit resources.
</P>
<P>
The biggest chunk of the budget went to the social services
sector with a total allocation of 159.4 billion pesos (3.7 billion
dollars), or 44.1 percent, Barican said.
</P>
<P>
The social services sector was followed by the economic sector
with 94.6 billion pesos (2.2 billion dollars); the general public
sector, 77.2 billion pesos (1.8 billion dollars); the defense,
30.2 billion pesos (702 million dollars) and other sectors, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
