<HEADLINE> Cambodian Opposition Protest Against Election Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The opposition parties of
Cambodia organized a large demonstration here on Sunday morning,
protesting at the results of the election despite Thursday night's
deadly grenade attack and a Ministry of Interior ban.
</P>
<P>
Many people held placards which wrote with slogans such as
"Funcinpec and Sam Rainsy Party Unites to Rebuild the Country!"
"Cambodian People Votes for Democracy!" "Recognize the Results of
Election Is to Betray People's Will!" "Our Votes Were Stolen!"
</P>
<P>
Organizers said that about 12,000 people took part in the
demonstration, which was called by the National United Front of
Funcinpec, the Sam Rainsy Party (SRP), the Son Sann Party,
Cambodian Neutral Party and six other small parties.
</P>
<P>
Sam Rainsy addressed the rally, demanding for investigation
into election fraud and asked the Cambodian People's Party (CPP)
to change the premier candidate from Second Prime Minister Hun Sen
to some other people such as CPP President Chea Sim or Co-Interior
Minister Sar Kheng.
</P>
<P>
Under Cambodia's Constitution, Hun Sen, candidate of the CPP,
is expected to head the next coalition government as his party, in
accordance with the results announced by the National Election
Committee, won the country's general elections held on July 26,
1998.
</P>
<P>
However, the main opposition political parties -- the Funcinpec
and the SRP -- had been refusing to accept the results and
insisted that the National Election Committee and the
Constitutional Council must investigate alleged election
irregularities before the formation of next government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
