<HEADLINE> More Overseas Firms Invest in China's Guizhou Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- More overseas companies have
invested in southwest China's Guizhou Province this year, official
figures indicate.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou, which is among the most economically under-developed
places in China, approved 36 overseas-funded enterprises in the
first half of this year, up 20 percent from the same period last
year. Eighteen of the enterprises were wholly funded by overseas
investors.
</P>
<P>
The 36 overseas-funded enterprises involve a total registered
capital of 86.34 million U.S. dollars, of which 80.57 million
U.S. dollars are from overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Overseas companies began to invest in Guizhou in the
mid-1980s. Currently, Guizhou has more than 1,080 overseas-funded
enterprises, with a total investment worth 2.35 billion U.S.
dollars and paid-in overseas investment hitting 1.15 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors in Guizhou mainly come from Hong Kong,
Macao, and countries in southeast Asia, Europe and America. They
invest in sectors including manufacturing, mining, construction,
agriculture, forestry, animal husbandry, fish farming, geological
prospecting, transportation, telecommunications and real estate.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
