<HEADLINE> Caracas Stock Exchange plunges in One Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Caracas Stock Exchange
closed 22 percent lower this weekend than the previous week,
accumulating a loss of 895.30 units with all the work days of the
week closed with losses.
</P>
<P>
The Caracas stock market registered its lowest level of the
last 28 months on Thursday with a 9.31 percent fall (363.82
points) to close at 3,460.64 points.
</P>
<P>
Stock brokers attributed the market fall to the lack of
confidence of investors in the Venezuelan national market.
</P>
<P>
They said the political crisis in Russia, where the State Duma
requested President Boris Yeltsin to resign, has sent shockwaves
across the European and U.S. markets, and was another reason for
the Venezuelan market collapse.
</P>
<P>
"The Russian crisis affected the international markets, and
Venezuela was not spared," said one broker.
</P>
<P>
Although the Venezuelan economic minister has tried to
stabilize the market, saying that there is no imminent devaluation
of the Venezuelan currency nor exchange control, investors
continue leaving the country, reports said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Venezuelan international reserves dropped by
3.64 billion dollars to 14.17 billion dollars by August, according
to the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
More than 700 million dollars of foreign capital had fled the
Venezuelan market from August 12 to 21, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
