<DOCNO> XIE19980823.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Caribbean Forum Ends Meeting on Promoting Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Caribbean Forum (Cariforum)
concluded its two-day meeting in Santo Domingo, capital of the
Dominican Republic, Saturday, with a joint declaration stressing the
region's integration in face of economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
The Cariforum, attended by 16 members and Cuba as its observer,
officially accepted Cuba as its full member, recognizing the
country is "part of the Caribbean family."
</P>
<P>
The joint declaration warns that the globalization process is
generating fundamental changes to the region's economies and
increasing the risk of excluding the smallest and most vulnerable
from rapid growth.
</P>
<P>
It points to the burden of foreign debts as a major obstacle to
the region's economic development and social stability.
</P>
<P>
While acknowledging the positive role of the World Trade
Organization, the Cariforum expressed concerns about a fair
distribution of the benefits of trade globalization and
liberalization, which it says must take into account the bigger
needs of less developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The forum urged its members to actively participate in the
negotiations of the Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA) to
secure the interests of smaller economies and their full
engagement.
</P>
<P>
The Caribbean countries voiced their disappointment with the
failure by the United States to approve a legislation guaranteeing
Caribbean producers the equality with their counterparts in
Mexico, Canada and the United States -- members of the North
America Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
They reiterated the policy to strengthen cooperation with
Central American countries, noting that the two regions had a lot
in common in their concerns about relations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Santo Domingo declaration also reaffirmed the region's
support for environment protection and commitment to concerted
actions against drug trafficking and abuse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
