<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Muslim Groups Furious Over U.S. Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Muslim groups in Sri Lanka are
angry over the recent United States' attacks on Sudan and
Afghanistan, Muslim groups sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that any acts of terrorism in any part of the
world should be condemned. "If the U.S. action is part of a global
effort to combat terrorism, the American should have first, bombed
Israel where state-sponsored terrorism is practiced," the sources
added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. missile attacks on Sudan and Afghanistan have violated
international law and basic human rights, they noted.
</P>
<P>
Washington on Thursday launched missile strikes on alleged
terrorist targets in Afghanistan and Sudan in response to the twin
bombings on August 7 in Kenya and Tanzania, which killed 257
people and injured more than 5,000 others.
</P>
<P>
General secretary of the Sri Lankan Muslim Welfare Association
(SLMWA) A. Shaul Hameed said here Saturday, "the SLMWA strongly
condemns acts of terrorism in any part of the world. But we must
also express our shock and dismay over the indiscriminate bombing
by the U.S. in Afghanistan and Sudan."
</P>
<P>
Several other Muslim parties have also condemned the U.S.
missile attacks, saying the U.S. action was disrespectful and
disregard for international norms.
</P>
<P>
They called on the United nations to take immediate action
against the U.S. for its attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
