<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke082310 - Roundup: Bangladesh's New Jute Policy Awaits Approval </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi Jute
Ministry-drafted new jute policy is awaiting Cabinet approval,
which emphasizes on privatization of public sector jute mills to
get rid of staggering losses and revitalize of the important
foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
The cumulative loss incurred by the country's 33 public sector
jute mills reached 23.16 million taka (bout 492.8 million U.S.
dollars) till the end of July 1996-June 1997 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Ministry said it was necessary to gradually
transfer the public sector jute mills to private entrepreneurs and
free the mills from huge losses, according to the draft jute
policy.
</P>
<P>
The current jute policy needs a timely reform to boost jute
goods production and export, Jute Ministry sources stated.
</P>
<P>
The policy was last revised during the 1988-89 fiscal year, for
 some of its contents were not suitable to the changing
circumstances in the jute industrial environment.
</P>
<P>
After evaluating the overall situation in the jute sector, the
new policy framers identified two key factors that cause losses in
jute production -- one is the continuous downtrend in jute demand
and lower prices of jute in the international market, the other is
the higher jute-goods production cost than the selling prices.
</P>
<P>
The price of raw jute declined to 40 dollars from 60 dollars
per bale (180 kilograms) last year in the international market.
And due to this reason, the earnings declined by 21 percent though
Bangladesh exported more jute last year than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The government should continue its privatization policy of the
state-owned jute mills, and the mills which would not be possible
to sell out should be liquidated, the policy framers said.
</P>
<P>
They also suggested to produce jute goods to keep consistency
with the international market, and according to the current
demand, production of jute goods should be kept below 0.5 million
tons per year.
</P>
<P>
In this connection, out of a total 26,000 looms at 33 public
sector mills, the Bangladesh Jute Mills Corporation (BJMC) would
only need to operate 15,000 to 20,000 looms to produce the
above-said amount.
</P>
<P>
Giving an outline of the jute production in the country, the
draft policy says that around 4.8 million bales (1 bale is 180
kilograms) of jute would be produced from about 0.48 million
hectares of land in the 1998-99 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The total availability of jute will stand at 6.187 million
bales including last year's carry-over of 1.387 million bales, and
out of these, 3.125 million bales would be necessary for local
consumption while around 2 million bales would be exported, with
the remaining 1.062 million bales being stored for next year.
</P>
<P>
The earnings from raw jute export have been estimated to be
around 4 billion taka (about 85.11 million dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
Around 400,000 tons of jute goods will be exported, earning 12
billion taka (about 255.3 million dollars), the new policy
predicts.
</P>
<P>
During last fiscal year, Bangladesh's jute goods export and
earnings faced a short fall of target by 24 percent and 26 percent
respectively. The targets were to export 482,000 tons of jute
goods from which to earn 14.87 billion taka (about 316.4 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The new policy also gives emphasis on diversification and
increasing the production of high quality jute.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh launched a project styled "comprehensive jute
production and marketing" in March 1997 to increase production of
high-quality jute. Around 85,000 bales of higher quality jute were
produced during the year 1997-98 though the target was fixed at
120,000 bales under the project.
</P>
<P>
Jute is the main cash crop in the country, with about 25
percent of the total 127 million-population involving in the
jute-related activities. And around 0.25 million workers,
employees and 3 million growers directly depend on the jute
sector, and another 100,000 traders earn their livelihood from
jute business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
