<HEADLINE> Colombian Stock Markets Collapse, Dollar Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's Bogota
Stock Exchange Index (IBB) and Medellin Stock Exchange Index
(IBOMED) dropped steadily this week, but the collapse intensified
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The IBB slid by 5.96 percent and the IBOMED by 4.30 percent at
the close of Friday's transactions, compared with 3.34 and 2.96
respectively a week ago.
</P>
<P>
The dollar price increased by 3.5 percent in the past week,
going from 1,384.50 pesos on August 14 to 1,429.00 on August 21.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts described the turbulence as an expected
consequence of the Asian and Russian currency crises as well as
slower growth in the region.
</P>
<P>
Investment dropped by 18 percent in the first half of the year
in Latin America and a high of 40 percent in Colombia, according
to Burson-Marsteller, an international consulting firm covering 32
emerging markets in six regions in the world.
</P>
<P>
Banco de la Republica, Colombia's central bank, attributed the
rise in the dollar value to a growing demand by the real sector of
the economy, especially foreign funds that bought 47 million
dollars, and the intermediate financiers who decided to strengthen
their position in the U.S. currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
