<HEADLINE> U.N. to Pull out Staff from Afghanistan: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has decided
to withdraw all its staff from Afghanistan following the killing
of its military adviser in an attack by unidentified gunmen in
Kabul on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The English daily The Frontier Post quoted authentic sources as
saying Sunday the U.N. has also informed the Taliban authorities
and the Pakistani government of its decision to pull out all its
staff from the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
"The decision (on Saturday) is apparently driven by the
deteriorating security environment in Afghanistan, which is
manifested in the killing of U.N. military advisor Lt-Col. Carmine
Calo," the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Also on Saturday, ACBAR, a joint body of about 674 registered
non-governmental organizations working in Afghanistan, was
reported to have called back its volunteers and officials from the
war-battered country.
</P>
<P>
According to the report most Americans and other foreigners
working for ACBAR had already left Peshawar, capital of Pakistan's
North West Frontier Province, for Islamabad on Friday while the
remaining few departed on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Islamabad-based U.N. representative for Afghanistan, James
Cobby, handed a strongly-worded communique Saturday to the Taliban
militia, protesting the attacks on U.N. officers in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He warned the Taliban militia in Kabul that if it failed to
protect the U.N. personnel and property in Afghanistan, it would
be compelled to withdraw its staff from the country.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. representative also demanded stringent actions against
the culprits responsible for attacking the U.N. staff in Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Saturday, Carmine Calo, the military adviser of the
U.N. mission in Kabul, who along with another U.N. official had
received grievous injuries in a shooting attack in Kabul Friday,
succumbed to injuries.
</P>
<P>
The dead body of Carmine Calo, a 42-year-old Italian national,
was airlifted from Kabul to Islamabad Saturday afternoon in a U.N.
chartered plane.
</P>
<P>
Carmine Calo had received severe bullet wounds. Another U.N.
officer at the mission, French national Eric Lavertu, was also
injured in the attack on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Eric Lavertu was also evacuated from Kabul and is now under
treatment in Islamabad. The U.N. sources said that Lavertu is in
stable condition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
