<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shipping Row Ruled Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 23 (Xinhua) -- In response to an
anti-discrimination investigation launched recently by the US
Federal Maritime Commission (FMC), Chinese authorities have
expressed hope that such bilateral trade friction can be dealt
with on the basis of negotiation rather that tit-for-tat action.
</P>
<P>
"We are not willing to retaliate in view of the progress the
two sides have made in maritime relations," a spokesman with the
Ministry of Communications told Business Weekly of "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
The ministry spokesman said US shipping companies have enjoyed
fair treatment in accordance with Chinese laws and
regulations. "We have offered US shipping companies full
most-favored nation status for their operations in China," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sea-Land and APL, the only two US shipping operators in China,
operate services on 12 shipping routes and have established four
wholly-owned subsidiaries in the country's ports.
</P>
<P>
The issues at stake include US shippers' inability to open
branch offices in China and a Chinese rule that foreign shippers
must get official permission or licenses to open new liner
shipping routes.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that as a developing country, China has to
open up its shipping market gradually since the country's
fledgling sectors need a transitional period. The threat of
sanctions from the FMC could strain maritime relations between the
giant trading powers.
</P>
<P>
Last December, US and Chinese negotiators reached a tentative
agreement to mutually improve port access. China promised to
approve six new shipping routes for US companies and Sea-Land's
co-operative project in Tianjin, while the United States engaged
to give greater priority to China's shipping operators.
</P>
<P>
China endorsed the six new routes early this year and is
preparing to approve the Tianjin project, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"But it hinges on the operational progress of China's shipping
companies, which the US side has pledged to foster," he said.
</P>
<P>
China Ocean Shipping Companies Group (Cosco), the country's
biggest shipping operator, is still not able to operate and
compete freely and openly in the United States, said Sun Jiakang,
general manager of the group's transportation department.
</P>
<P>
"Our company is till considered a controlled carrier in the
United States," said Sun.
</P>
<P>
The United States has listed 37 foreign carriers, mostly from
communist countries, as "controlled," meaning their bidding prices
take 30 days to be approved while common carriers need only 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives passed the S414 Act this
month, which will impose discriminatory conditions on China's
shipping operators when it becomes effective.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. delegation led by Administrator Clyde Hart of the
Transportation Department's Maritime Administration will visit
China next week to restart negotiations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
