<HEADLINE> Contiguglia Elected U.S. Soccer Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Dr. Bob Contiguglia
succeeded outgoing American soccer head Alan Rothenberg to
become the new president of the U.S. Soccer Federation (USSF) in
an election in Wailea, Hawaii, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Contiguglia, 55, beat outgoing USSF executive vice president
Larry Monaco with 57.6 percent of the vote of USSF members.
Monaco received 42.4 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
Contiguglia was seen generally as the candidate that was more
supportive of continuing to build on the gains of the
professional division, meaning essentially Major League Soccer,
and the national teams.
</P>
<P>
Rothenberg, the head of the 1994 World Cup organizing
committee and the founder of MLS, is stepping down after
completing his second four-year term as USSF president.
</P>
<P>
Under USSF bylaws, no one can serve as president for more than
two terms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
