<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Myanmar, Thailand Strengthen Trade and </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The 50th anniversary of the
establishment of diplomatic relations between Myanmar and Thailand
which falls on August 24, has witnessed significant achievements
of close trade and economic cooperation between the two southeast
Asian nations in the past 50 years especially in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In May 1997, former Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh
visited Myanmar, setting the stage for enhancing trade and
economic cooperation and good neighborly relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on border crossing was then signed and notes on
jurisdiction over the Thai-Myanmar Friendship Bridge on the Moei
(Thaungyin) River exchanged, signifying a step forward in
facilitating trade, transport and communications between the two
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The Friendship Bridge, which links border towns of Myawaddy
(Myanmar) and Maesot (Thailand), was opened later in August in the
same year.
</P>
<P>
In last December, foreign ministers of Myanmar and Thailand
agreed at the 4th meeting of the Myanmar-Thai Joint Commission for
Bilateral Cooperation in Bangkok to enhance their bilateral
cooperation in the sectors of culture, health, education,
technology, agriculture, tourism, trade, investment,
communications, energy, fishery and drug control.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, one of Myanmar's major trading partners, began border
trade with the country in March 1996 at three border points --
Maesai-Tachilek, Maesod-Myawaddy and Ranong-Kawthoung.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, bilateral trade including
border trade stood at 330 million U.S. dollars in the 1997-98
fiscal year which ended in March, up from 289 million dollars in
1996-97. The balance of trade was in Thailand's favor.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, one of the leading foreign investors in Myanmar,
ranked the third after Britain and Singapore with 1.16 billion
dollars in 42 projects out of the 7-billion-dollar total foreign
investment at the end of March this year. The investment covers
such sectors as oil and gas, hotels and tourism, livestock
breeding and fishery, industrial estate and transport.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's investment was also highlighted by its involvement
in the development of two Myanmar offshore natural gas fields, the
Yadana and the Yetagun, where gas is due to be sold to Thailand
later this year and the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Thailand's private sector began to join in the
infrastructural development of Myanmar's Hlaingtharya Industrial
Zone in Yangon in April 1997, bringing the zone to the third
foreign-invested industrial zone status after the Mingaladon and
the Thanlyin-Kyauktan.
</P>
<P>
On the telecommunications sector, Myanmar prepares to use the
Thaicom satellite transponder for its domestic satellite
communication services under a lease contract with the Sinawatra
Group of Thailand initiated in March this year, thus replacing the
one leased earlier from Hong Kong's Asiasat-1 and 2 for its
telecast of the military-run Myawaddy TV station.
</P>
<P>
With regard to transport links, Thailand has granted two loans
of 150 million and 11.5 million U.S. dollars respectively for
building Myanmar's new Mandalay International Airport and
upgrading the Tachilek-Kengtung road which leads up to Bangkok
through Chiang Rai.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also plan to develop two deep seaports -- one
in Thailand's Bagan Saphan on the gulf of Thailand and the other
in Myanmar's Bokpyin area along the Andaman Sea.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Myanmar and Thailand initiated an agreement on
cooperation in tourism, which opened up more opportunities in
cultural exchange. This is seen as a contribution to fostering and
enhancing of closer relationship between the two countries and two
peoples.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
