<DOCNO> XIE19980823.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mine Closure Scheme to Overcome Coal Glut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 23 (Xinhua) -- China plans to shut down 22,000
small coal mines operating without production licenses by 2000,
today's "China Daily" quoted a leading official with the State
Coal Industry Bureau as saying.
</P>
<P>
The mines to be closed include those that produce low quality
coal and pollute the environment. Workers laid off as a result of
the closures will be transferred to other industries and
services, according to Wang Xianzheng, deputy director of the
State Coal Industry Bureau.
</P>
<P>
China's coal stockpile had reached 65.58 million tons by the
end of June, 9.35 million tons higher than at the beginning of the
year. Wang attributed the serious glut to rampant production by
small coal mines.
</P>
<P>
The closures are expected to reduce annual coal output by 200
million tons and balance demand and supply on the domestic market,
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The State Economic and Trade Commission, the State Coal
Industry Bureau and other State administrations are co-operating
in the drafting of specific measures to implement the closure
decision, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
In tandem with the shutting down of small mines, the State
Council has decided to transfer supervision rights for 94 State
key coal mines from the former Ministry of Coal Industry to
provincial governments.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China's coal industry finally put an end to the
serious losses of the 1984-96 period, with the key State coal
mines earning 200 million yuan (24.1 million US dollars) in net
profits.
</P>
<P>
But in the first half of this year, the key coal firms reported
aggregate deficits of 1.75 billion yuan. The formidable losses
resulted from a flagging market caused by massive oversupply of
coal.
</P>
<P>
China has 94 key State coal mines, 2,500 local State coal mines
and 75,000 township and village coal mines. Some small mines have
become black sheep in the sector because they disrupt the market,
squander resources and bring about numerous fatalities, Wang
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
