<HEADLINE> Ivanisevic, Kucera Advance to Pilot Pen Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Eighth seed Goran Ivanisevic
of Croatia dumped fifth seed Yevgeny Kafelnikov of Russia for the
seventh straight time today to advance to the final of the
870,000 U.S. dollars Pilot Pen international tennis tournament in
Connecticut, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Ivanisevic improved to 9-2 lifetime versus Kafelnikov with a
6-3, 6-4 victory and will play seventh seed Karol Kucera of
Slovakia in Sunday's final. Kucera upset fourth seed and 1995
finalist Richard Krajicek of the Netherlands 7-6 (8-6), 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Ivanisevic almost did not start the match after feeling pain
in his left shoulder during warmups, but he was able to take the
court afte taking pain killers and undergoing a cream massage.
</P>
<P>
Kucera is in his third final of the season and second on
hardcourts. He won in Sydney in January but Krajicek predicted an
Ivanisevic victory in Sunday's final.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Kucera broke in the fourth game of the second
set when Krajicek hit a backhand volley into the net. He was servi
ng for the match at 5-4 but made two double faults, the last
giving the game to Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
"I knew that his serve is maybe not so good, so I knew he was
going to come out and try to break me to win the match because he
prefers that," Krajicek said. "Iknew it was a big game at 5-4. I
felt if I can hold on maybe that was a shot."
</P>
<P>
However, the Dutchman could not hold on in the next game,
dropping his serve and the match. 
</P>
