<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insurance Companies Pay Out to Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Insurance companies
reacted quickly to settle compensations claims arising from the
the heavy floods sweeping China Since July.
</P>
<P>
Today's Business Weekly of China Daily reported that the
People's Insurance Company of China Group (PICC Group) has
provided advance payments totalling 1 billion yuan (120 million
U.S. dollars) to the flood-hit areas by August 20.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said other big companies as Ping An Insurance
Compay and Pacific Insurance Company are also reported to have
offered huge sum of compensation, although specific figures are
not available yet.
</P>
<P>
The floods had destroyed 5.58 million houses, damaged another
12.05 million and forced 13.8 million people to move to safe
places by August 9.
</P>
<P>
The floods on the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River
had caused at least 39.7 billion yuan (4.7 billion U.S. dollars)
in economic losses to Hunan, Hubei and Jiangxi provinces by August
9.
</P>
<P>
The PICC Property, an insurance arm of the PICC Group, has
received claims totalling 3.1 billion yuan (373.4 million
U.S. dollars) from insured enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The PICC Group branches in the flooded provinces have sent more
than 3,000 agents to the flood-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
The Hubei branch of the PICC Property on August 7 paid
compensation to 76 enterprises and institutions.
</P>
<P>
Experts said compensation for flood losses has been rising
sharply in recent years. In coastal areas and provinces along the
major rivers, compensation for flood losses has accounted for 50 to
80 percent of all insurance payouts.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts believed that Chinese companys' awareness of
the role of insurance in lessening risks is still weak.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
