<HEADLINE> Thai PM Pledges to Offer Help for Laid-off Employees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai has promised to ensure assistance for the laid-off
employees of the Bangkok Bank of Commerce (BBC) which was closed
under the government's latest reform package, the Bangkok Post
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted the prime minister as saying that he had
ordered government agencies concerned to help the BBC staff who
will lose their jobs when the bank is closed and merged with the
state-run Krung Thai Bank.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said he was willing to meet representatives of the BBC
employees and listen to their complaints on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 BBC employees rallied last Wednesday at the
headquarters of the bank, urging the government to employ them at
other state-owned banks, to waive tax on their severance pay and
pensions without any deductions for loans they had taken.
</P>
<P>
Sources from Krung Thai Bank, which is taking over the deposits
and good debts from the BBC, said the bank would absorb 1,000 of
BBC's 5,000-strong staff.
</P>
<P>
BBC staff to be made redundant will remain in their jobs until
November 15 and those laid off would be given 10 months of their
salary in severance pay plus provident fund and pension. 
</P>
