<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The third flood crest on the Songhua River passed yesterday
through Harbin, a major heavy industrial city in China's
northernmost province of Heilongjiang, with the water level
climbing to 120.89 meters, 0.84 meters higher than the historic
high, while the water flow rate reaching 17,300 cubic meters per
second.
</P>
<P>
The floods also broke the third line of defense for
safeguarding Daqing, China's top oilfield Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Over one million army men and local residents have been working
for safeguarding Harbin, the Daqing oilfield and other big cities
in the province.
</P>
<P>
-- More than 230,000 People's Liberation Army (PLA) men are
working at the flood fighting frontiers at the Yangtze River,
Songhua River and Nenjiang River.
</P>
<P>
The PLA Headquarters of the General Staff, General Logistics
Department, General Political Department and General Armament
Department have supplied the PLA flood fighters with large amount
of necessary goods valued at over 100 million yuan (12 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, visited
flood-stricken areas in central China's Hubei Province Friday.
</P>
<P>
He heard reports of local party and government leaders, toured
the Yangtze River embankments and chatted with flood fighters and
victims, conveying the regards of the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), the State Council and CPC General
Secretary of Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
-- The sixth flood crest on the Yangtze River has reached
Jiujiang in east China's Jiangxi Province and it will pass the
city by this afternoon. More than 30,000 PLA men and armed police
are working together with local residents to defend the major
embankments of the city.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- In response to an anti-discrimination investigation launched
recently by the U.S. Federal Maritime Commission (FMC), Chinese
authorities have expressed hope that such bilateral trade friction
can be dealt with on the basis of negotiation rather than
tit-for-tat action.
</P>
<P>
"We are not willing to retaliate in view of the progress the
two sides have made in maritime relations", a spokesman with the
Ministry of Communications told Business Weekly of China Daily.
</P>
<P>
-- China plans to shut down 22,000 small coal mines operating
without production licenses by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The mines to be closed include those that produce low quality
cool and pollute the environment. 
</P>
