<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wuhan Steel Complex Acting as Steel Bulwark Against Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Wuhan Iron and Steel Complex
in the capital of central China's Hubei Province, one of the
hardest-hit regions in this flood season, has played an
indispensable role in combating the floods.
</P>
<P>
The plant has been responsible for the safety of a
7.5-kilometer-long Yangtze River embankment, which is one-third of
the river length that runs through the city, and also its most
dangerous section.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,560 plant personnel have been fortifying and manning the
bank in shifts around-the-clock since flooding hit the city in
June.
</P>
<P>
In addition to manpower, the plant has donated 2.8 million yuan
for disaster relief and provided 8,000 cubic meters of material
for filling levee breaches.
</P>
<P>
The flood-control effort, however, has not held up production,
although torrential rains and the suspension of navigation on the
Yangtze have created harsh difficulties. This has been attributed
to the plant's early precautions such has accumulating enough raw
materials in May and June to sustain a month and a half of
production.
</P>
<P>
In July, the plant surpassed its production targets
for the output of iron, steel and rolled steel.
</P>
<P>
A few other companies in Wuhan have also maintained
performance while contributing to the flood-control battle.
</P>
<P>
A Sino-French joint venture, Shenlong (Citroen) Automotive
Co. Ltd., responsible for the safety of a more than
one-kilometer-long dike, saw its output in the first seven months
increase by 33 percent, and turnovers by 26.8 percent over the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
By August 14, Citroen had donated two vehicles and 959,000 yuan
to the city's flood control efforts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980823.0168 </DOCNO>
