<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, August 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- President Bill Clinton on Saturday launched a new
offensive against U.S. arch-foe Osama bin Laden by blocking all
financial transactions between U.S. companies and the Saudi
millionaire, accused by Washington of masterminding the bombings
of two U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"I have just signed an executive order directing the Treasury
to block all financial transactions between the bin Laden
terrorist group and American persons and companies," Clinton said
in the weekly radio address. He also urged other governments to do
the same.
</P>
<P>
"We must not allow sanctuary for terrorism, not for terrorists
or for their money," he added. "It takes money, lots of it, to
build the network bin Laden has. We'll do our best to see that he
has less of it."
</P>
<P>
But some of senior officials admitted Clinton's order was
unlikely to have an impact on much of bin Laden's fortune,
estimated at 300 million U.S. dollars, because they did not
believe much of his assets were subject to U.S. jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
But they said the United States would ask some of its allies to
take the similar action. (US-Strikes-Clinton-Sanctions)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl Saturday held a telephone
conservations with Russian President Boris Yeltsin and expressed
worry about the escalation of violence in Yugoslavia's province of
Kosovo, a German government spokesman said Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
During his half-an-hour telephone conservations with Yeltsin,
Kohl expressed particular worry about the sufferings of civilians
in the Kosovo conflict as well as the growing number of refugees
from that region.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed disappointment about the failure of the
Yugoslav government in particular in delivering their promises to
end the conflict.
</P>
<P>
In the telephone talks, the two leaders also discussed the
recent Russian financial crisis, with Kohl expressing the hope
that Russia could manage to restore investors' confidence as soon
as possible, the German spokesman said. (Germany-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Tens of thousands of people packed into the streets
of Omagh on Saturday to remember the victims of last week's bomb.
</P>
<P>
Men, women and children crowded the narrow streets in front of
the courthouse for an open-air ceremony attended by British and
Irish political leaders from the Catholic and Protestant
communities.
</P>
<P>
The blast, the worst incident in the past 30 years in Northern
Ireland, has killed 28 people and injured 220. (N.Ireland-Victims)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Sudan Saturday asked the U.N. Security Council to
hold an urgent meeting on the recent U.S. air raid on an alleged
terrorist-related site in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the Security Council, the Sudanese Ministry of
Foreign Relations asked the Security Council to shoulder its
responsibility under the U.N. Charter and condemn the
U.S. aggression, Sudanese News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., accusing Sudan of sponsoring international terrorism,
fired cruise missiles Thursday night at a pharmaceutical factory
in Khartoum in what it claimed retaliation for the twin bombings
of its embassies in Kenya and Tanzania on August 7.
</P>
<P>
More than 250 people were killed and 5,000 others wounded in
the bombings.
</P>
<P>
In the message, Sudan requested that the United Nations set up
a technical fact-finding committee to probe the claims of the
United States and adopt measures to prevent the repetition of
similar strikes in the future.
</P>
<P>
Such actions are "grave behavior and flagrant violation of the
U.N. Charter," said the message. (Sudan-UN-US Raid)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- The floods are still flowing at a high-water level
Saturday in China, a sign of continuing difficulty in the
anti-disaster effort.
</P>
<P>
The third flood crest on the Songhua River Saturday passed through
Harbin, a major heavy-industrial city in China's northernmost
province of Heilongjiang, with the water level climbing to 120.89
meters, 0.84 meters higher than the historic high, while the water
flow rate reaching 17,300 cubic meters per second by 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The water level of the city has not yet lowered much, according
to evening reports from China Central Television (CCTV).
Authorities attributed this to poor distribution on the river
section, noting that the width there ranges from 1-to-10 km, which
adds difficulties for the flow of the floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
"It is at a crucial moment to counter the flooding," said an
on-the-spot water control expert. A total of 400,000 soldiers and
civilians are safeguarding the city.
</P>
<P>
The sixth flood crest on the Yangtze River has reached Jiujiang
in east China's Jiangxi Province. It will have passed through
Jiujiang by Sunday afternoon. The water level at the city stood at
22.46 m at 2 p.m. Saturday, 0.04 m more than Friday's level,
according to the latest information from the State Flood Control
and Drought Relief Headquarters (SFCDRH). (China-Roundup-Today's
Floods) 
</P>
