<HEADLINE> Slovakia's Foreign Debts Hit Historical High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Slovak foreign debts soared
to 11.2 billion U.S. dollars at the end of May this year, the
highest since 1993 when the country gained independence, according
to news reports reaching here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
An official with the National Bank of Slovakia was quoted by
reports as saying that two thirds of the debts were short-term
loans that have to be repaid in three years, constituting
tremendous pressure on the Slovak economy.
</P>
<P>
Foreign debts have currently accounted for more than 50 percent
of the country's gross domestic product, far above the warning
level of 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia owed 3.7 billion dollars in foreign debts in 1993,
which shot up to 7.8 billion in 1996 and 10.7 billion in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
