<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood-Hit Hubei Keeps Fast Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Flood-stricken Hubei Province in
central China registered a fast economic growth in the first half
of this year, official figures showed.
</P>
<P>
Though suffering huge economic losses from the worst flooding
of the Yangtze River in 45 years, gross domestic product of the
province expanded by 9.5 percent in the period, 2.5 percentage
points higher than the national average, according to the
provincial statistical bureau.
</P>
<P>
The province's output of summer grains totaled 5.017 million
tons, the third largest harvest in the history, while the
incremental output of industries grew by 9.9 percent, two
percentage points higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, fiscal revenue and foreign trade also
witnessed remarkable growth, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
Last month when flooding became worse, the provincial
government asked all localities to concentrate on flood control
and facilitate industrial and agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
In Wuhan, the provincial capital, industrial output totaled 5.9
billion yuan in July, a year-on-year increase of 11.82 percent
which was even faster than the first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has projected an economic growth
target of 12 percent for the year 1998. Local officials said that
the province will strive to overcome the difficulties brought
about by the flooding and work hard to meet the target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
