<HEADLINE> Drechsler Wins 4th Straight European Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Heike Drechsler won her fourth
straight European Championship title in the same event when she
captured the gold medal in the women's long jump here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Colin Jackson of Britain won his third successive win in the
men's 110-meter hurdles in a championship record of 13.02
seconds, beating his own mark of 13.04 set in the previous meet
four years ago.
</P>
<P>
Drechsler soared 7.16 meters, the fourth longest jump in the
world this year, behind three by American Marion Jones, whose
best is 7.31.
</P>
<P>
Fiona May of Italy, Olympic silver medalist and bronze
medalist in last year's world championships, took the silver with
a jump of 7.11. World champion Lydmila Galkina of Russia was
third at 7.06.
</P>
<P>
Christine Arron anchored France to a victory in the women's
4x100-meter relay and won her second gold medal of competition.
</P>
<P>
The 100-meter champion pulled her team from third to first
with an astonishing last leg. The French won in 42.59 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Darren Campbell and Doug Walker also picked up their second
golds when they ran in the winning British team in the men's
4x100 relay. Campbell was the 100-meter champion, Walker the 200
gold medalist.
</P>
<P>
The British foursome prevailed in a time of 38.52. France took
the silver in 38.87, while Poland was third in 38.98.
</P>
<P>
In the men's hurdles, Jackson cruised home without being
pushed, but failed in his declared goal of going under 13 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Falk Balzer of Germany won the silver in 13.12, while Robin
Korving of the Netherlands took the bronze in 13.20.
</P>
<P>
Maksim Tarasov of Russia cleared 5.81 meters to win the men's
pole vault. Tim Lobinger of Germany was second with the same
height but with more attempts overall, while Jean Galfione of
France, the Olympic champion, had to settle for bronze at 5.76.
</P>
<P>
In the morning, Stefano Baldini overcame rainy and windy
conditions to lead an Italian medal sweep in the men's marathon
in two hours 12 minutes one seconds.
</P>
<P>
Fellow Italian Danilo Goffi was second in 2:12.11, and another
Italian, Vincenzo Modica, took the bronze in 2:12.53.
</P>
<P>
Wilson Kipketer, world champion and record-holder, did just
enough to qualify for the final in the men's 800 by finishing
third in his semifinal heat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
