<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Coffee Output Expected to Drop by 6.3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Costa Rican coffee output
may drop by some 200,000 46-kilo bags during the 1998-99 season,
down 6.3 percent from the 1997-98 figure.
</P>
<P>
The estimate was made by the Coffee Institute in a report
published Saturday about the coffee harvest that began in july and
will be completed in March or April of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Executive officer of the institute Guillermo Canet explained
that coffee production is cyclical and based on this theory, the
1997-1998 output was 3.2 million bags and the 1998-99 harvest is
initially estimated at 3 million bags.
</P>
<P>
He said coffee production may have been affected by "El Nino,"
especially in the main coffee producing provinces of Alajuela and
Heredia.
</P>
<P>
The main effect was the delay in the start of the rainy season,
which affected first the blossoming and then the growth of the
plant.
</P>
<P>
The official said the estimated drop in coffee harvest in Costa
Rica and other countries in Latin America like Mexico, and
especially one of the biggest producers, Indonesia, may trigger a
rebound of coffer prices in the international coffee market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
