<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Owen Denied by Arsenal in English Premier League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- World Cup legend boy Michael
Owen, who signed a new five-year deal with Liverpool, failed to
reproduce his scintillating World Cup form in a English Premier
league match against Arsenal on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old star was denied any genuine chances by the
defending champions' defence, which produced a typically assured
display even in the absence of skipper Tony Adams with food
poisoning.
</P>
<P>
And eventually it was another Liverpool's young man,
20-year-old Jamie Carragher who secured a point for his side 10
minutes from time.
</P>
<P>
Ray Parlour's long ball found the fast-moving Marc Overmars,
who squeezed his shot past Liverpool keeper Brad Friedel.
</P>
<P>
But Carragher, switched this season from midfield to the
center of defence, raced back to block the ball on the line.
</P>
<P>
It meant that the clash of the Frenchmen -- Liverpool's Gerard
Houllier and Arsenal's Arsene Wenger -- ended with a draw.
</P>
<P>
But Wenger would take more satisfaction from the result than
Houllier, in his first Premier league home match since joining
Liverpool as joint boss with Roy Evans.
</P>
<P>
Indeed the Gunners were so effective at thwarting Liverpool's
attacking instincts, that it was the visitors who ended up
producing the best moments of the first half.
</P>
<P>
Arsenal midfielder Parlour wasted the best chance of the match
by blazing over the bar from close range in the 34th minute after
Friedel had pulled off a stunning save to deny Nicolas Anelka.
</P>
<P>
Overmars came close to grabbing a winner ten minutes from time,
but after outpacing the defence, he beat Friedel only to see
Carragher block his shot on the line.
</P>
<P>
Liverpool rarely troubled David Seamen in the Arsenal goal
with Steve McManaman sending several speculative shots spinning
wide.
</P>
<P>
But the England goalkeeper did need the help of defender
Martin Keown in the 57th minute after he failed to hold a low
drive from Vegard Heggem. The ball ran loose to Karlheinz Riedle
who saw his effort blocked on the line by the England defender.
</P>
<P>
After the match, Wenger said: "They played against strong
strikers in Owen and Riedle ... their average age is 33 or more
and they still looked very good.
</P>
<P>
"That is down to experience, intelligence and motivation. My
dream would have been to have them ten years earlier," he said.
</P>
<P>
Liverpool joint boss Gerard Houllier was happy to take a point
from the match.
</P>
<P>
"I felt it was a fair draw, but we do need a bit more
composure and confidence on the ball," he said afterwards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
