<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands in N. Irish Town Omagh to Remember Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of people
packed into the streets of Omagh on Saturday to remember the
victims of last week's bomb.
</P>
<P>
Men, women and children crowded the narrow streets in front of
the courthouse for an open-air ceremony attended by British and
Irish political leaders from the Catholic and Protestant
communities.
</P>
<P>
"At this hour last Saturday, 28 good and deeply loved people,
one carrying twins awaiting birth, were alive in these
streets...This space within our town, where all our futures were
changed one week ago, is today a silent sanctuary of remembrance,
hearing the silence of the inner sanctuaries of broken hearts and
families," Catholic priest Kevin Mullan told the hushed crowd.
</P>
<P>
The blast, the worst incident in the past 30 years in Northern
Ireland, has killed 28 people and injured 220.
</P>
<P>
Mullan said each day and night had been filled with "horror,
pain and grief."
</P>
<P>
Huge red curtains draped the front of the 19th century
courthouse where 50,000 people gathered to observe a moment of
silence at 3.10 pm (1410 gmt) -- the moment a 225 kg car bomb
ripped through Omagh's busy shopping street.
</P>
<P>
Irish President Mary McAleese, Irish premier Bertie Ahern,
Britain's deputy prime minister John Prescott and Northern
Ireland's political leaders were among those who attended.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-five people are still being treated in hospital after
the blast. Fourteen of them are children, several are critically
injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
