<HEADLINE> Clinton Orders to Cut bin Laden's Financial Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Saturday launched a new offensive against U.S. arch-foe Osama bin
Laden by blocking all financial transactions between U.S.
companies and the Saudi millionaire, accused by Washington of
masterminding the bombings of two U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"I have just signed an executive order directing the Treasury
to block all financial transactions between the bin Laden
terrorist group and American persons and companies," Clinton said
in the weekly radio address. He also urged other governments to do
the same.
</P>
<P>
"We must not allow sanctuary for terrorism, not for terrorists
or for their money," he added. "It takes money, lots of it, to
build the network bin Laden has. We'll do our best to see that he
has less of it."
</P>
<P>
But some of senior officials admitted Clinton's order was
unlikely to have an impact on much of bin Laden's fortune,
estimated at $300 million, because they did not believe much of
his assets were subject to U.S. jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
But they said the United States would ask some of its allies to
take the similar action.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the United
States now had intelligence providing further proof that all six
militant training camps hit by missiles in Afghanistan sustained
"moderate to severe damage."
</P>
<P>
"Each of the six camps sustained some level of damage," McCurry
said.
</P>
<P>
Islamic radicals speaking for bin Laden insisted that, despite
Clinton's assertion of having "convincing" evidence of his role
in the August 7 bombings at the two embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania, he had nothing to do with the explosions that killed
more than 250 people and injured over 5,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
